WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:11.050 --> 00:00:12.420
&gt;&gt; Guha Shankar: Thank you all
very much for coming to part two

00:00:12.420 --> 00:00:13.910
for this lovely symposium.

00:00:13.910 --> 00:00:15.280
It's a terrific morning.

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:18.010
And we're going to move
right into panel two.

00:00:18.010 --> 00:00:21.190
It's called Culture Production,
Activism and a Creative Hub:

00:00:21.190 --> 00:00:22.810
The Drum and Spear Bookstore.

00:00:22.810 --> 00:00:25.330
Since we are talking about
cultural politics, region,

00:00:25.330 --> 00:00:27.310
geography, democracy
and all those things,

00:00:27.310 --> 00:00:31.000
we wanted to bring it
all the way home here

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:34.130
at the Library of Congress.

00:00:34.130 --> 00:00:37.380
And we're going to
start by saying

00:00:37.380 --> 00:00:38.730
that there were some bios.

00:00:38.730 --> 00:00:40.030
I believe they're out there.

00:00:40.030 --> 00:00:42.800
If not, you can actually dial
them up on your cell phones,

00:00:42.800 --> 00:00:45.070
iPhones, smartphones,
tablets, what have you.

00:00:45.070 --> 00:00:48.260
And we're going to start
with our panel here.

00:00:48.260 --> 00:00:49.560
Distinguished panel of folks,

00:00:49.560 --> 00:00:51.030
many of whom have
been interviewed here

00:00:51.030 --> 00:00:53.160
for the Civil Rights History
Project, a joint initiative

00:00:53.160 --> 00:00:55.650
of the Library of Congress
and National Museum

00:00:55.650 --> 00:00:57.570
of African American
History and Culture.

00:00:57.570 --> 00:01:02.080
And to my right, your left,
that's for the camera as well,

00:01:02.080 --> 00:01:06.000
Judy Richardson, activist, media
producer, longtime stalwart

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:09.590
of many artistic
productions here at DC

00:01:09.590 --> 00:01:11.140
and across the country.

00:01:11.140 --> 00:01:12.960
Next to her, Tony Gittens,
well-known to some of you

00:01:12.960 --> 00:01:16.880
as the director of DC's
Premier Film Festival.

00:01:16.880 --> 00:01:19.750
To my left, Jennifer Lawson,

00:01:19.750 --> 00:01:23.290
another media producer,
activist.

00:01:23.290 --> 00:01:25.450
To her left is Josh Davis.

00:01:25.450 --> 00:01:28.420
And we sort of inverted the
order because our final guest,

00:01:28.420 --> 00:01:30.760
Josh Davis, professor at
the University of Baltimore,

00:01:30.760 --> 00:01:34.380
author of aforementioned book
which I've held up for you --

00:01:34.380 --> 00:01:37.000
and he is available
for signatures

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:38.300
and what not later on.

00:01:38.300 --> 00:01:42.080
And all the way to his left
is Courtland Cox, activist,

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:47.100
organizer, political worker,
member of the DC government

00:01:47.100 --> 00:01:49.930
in many capacities over
the course of time.

00:01:49.930 --> 00:01:52.870
And we are very, very
thrilled to have them all here.

00:01:52.870 --> 00:01:55.230
I'm going to stop talking
at this moment and sit

00:01:55.230 --> 00:01:56.530
and do what John Fend did,

00:01:56.530 --> 00:01:58.550
which was to kind of
mediate everybody.

00:01:58.550 --> 00:02:03.560
And I'm going to begin by also
starting off with a film loop

00:02:03.560 --> 00:02:07.330
which will play in the
background as we're talking,

00:02:07.330 --> 00:02:10.050
and it gives you some sense
of what the cultural milieu

00:02:10.050 --> 00:02:16.000
and the social structure and
all those things of 1968 and so

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:18.380
on Washington DC
was as they speak.

00:02:18.380 --> 00:02:19.680
There are no particular --

00:02:19.680 --> 00:02:21.590
I think there will be some
references made to some

00:02:21.590 --> 00:02:22.890
of these photographs,

00:02:22.890 --> 00:02:24.990
but they'll not be
speaking directly with them.

00:02:24.990 --> 00:02:26.550
So Judy, if you would start.

00:02:26.550 --> 00:02:27.850
Thank you.

00:02:27.850 --> 00:02:29.150
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: Okie-dokie.

00:02:29.150 --> 00:02:30.450
Well, thank you,
everybody, and thank you,

00:02:30.450 --> 00:02:31.750
Guha, for introing us.

00:02:31.750 --> 00:02:33.970
Let me just say that for me,

00:02:33.970 --> 00:02:37.670
Drum and Spear bookstore was
a continuity of the work,

00:02:37.670 --> 00:02:41.680
a continuation of the
work that we did in SNCC.

00:02:41.680 --> 00:02:43.950
Expanding the awareness
of ourselves

00:02:43.950 --> 00:02:46.150
and of our power to
change the world.

00:02:46.150 --> 00:02:48.760
And Drum and Spear becomes
the largest African American

00:02:48.760 --> 00:02:50.430
bookstore in the country.

00:02:50.430 --> 00:02:52.320
Now when I first see the store,

00:02:52.320 --> 00:02:55.830
I had to go through
tear gas to get to it.

00:02:55.830 --> 00:02:57.580
It was May 1968.

00:02:57.580 --> 00:03:00.210
It was on 14th and
Fairmont Streets,

00:03:00.210 --> 00:03:02.390
and the street had just
recently been tear gassed

00:03:02.390 --> 00:03:03.690
after the rebellions

00:03:03.690 --> 00:03:06.480
that followed the
assassination of Dr. King.

00:03:06.480 --> 00:03:09.130
So I meet Tony Gittens,
this person here,

00:03:09.130 --> 00:03:11.530
who is the manager of the store.

00:03:11.530 --> 00:03:15.720
And we go through the tear
gas and he opens the door.

00:03:15.720 --> 00:03:21.550
And what I see is a
space with maybe three

00:03:21.550 --> 00:03:26.530
or four recently stained
bookcases and no books.

00:03:26.530 --> 00:03:30.750
So I had arrived in DC
just a few days before

00:03:30.750 --> 00:03:34.060
because my SNCC buddies had
asked me to come run the office

00:03:34.060 --> 00:03:37.090
for the parent company,
African American Resources, Inc.

00:03:37.090 --> 00:03:41.110
So I'd left DC where I'd been
attending Columbia University

00:03:41.110 --> 00:03:44.790
since returning to school
after three years on SNCC staff

00:03:44.790 --> 00:03:46.990
in Mississippi, Alabama,
Southwest Georgia.

00:03:46.990 --> 00:03:50.020
And I headed to DC with
my mattress on the roof

00:03:50.020 --> 00:03:53.920
of a car driven by Curtis
Hayes, another SNCC person

00:03:53.920 --> 00:03:57.100
who was involved in
setting up the store.

00:03:57.100 --> 00:04:00.510
Tony outlined to me
what needed to be done

00:04:00.510 --> 00:04:03.820
and the process for
getting there.

00:04:03.820 --> 00:04:05.200
He was the first person I saw.

00:04:05.200 --> 00:04:07.270
I knew that Courtland and
Charlie Cobb and a number

00:04:07.270 --> 00:04:09.300
of other people,
Jennifer, were involved.

00:04:09.300 --> 00:04:11.900
But Tony as the first person
that I see in the store

00:04:11.900 --> 00:04:13.400
through this tear gas, right?

00:04:13.400 --> 00:04:17.910
And so he outlines what has
to be done and the target date

00:04:17.910 --> 00:04:20.900
for the opening of the store,
which is just a month away.

00:04:20.900 --> 00:04:23.910
And I'm sitting there
looking, there are no books.

00:04:23.910 --> 00:04:27.660
So at some point we set up
an account with Bookazine

00:04:27.660 --> 00:04:29.220
which was book distributor.

00:04:29.220 --> 00:04:31.750
I actually remember
this, in New York City.

00:04:31.750 --> 00:04:36.270
And the bookstore had purchased
a VW van which I drove.

00:04:36.270 --> 00:04:38.610
So Tony and I drive
up to New York City.

00:04:38.610 --> 00:04:43.280
We get to Bookazine and there
is this incredible black

00:04:43.280 --> 00:04:45.070
salesperson at Bookazine.

00:04:45.070 --> 00:04:48.530
So we tell him about the
store and that you know,

00:04:48.530 --> 00:04:51.050
it's a black bookstore,
that it's going to be right

00:04:51.050 --> 00:04:52.830
in the heart of the
community in DC.

00:04:52.830 --> 00:04:54.600
And he gets so excited, right?

00:04:54.600 --> 00:04:57.650
We give him a list of books
that we were interested in.

00:04:57.650 --> 00:05:04.180
Books about the African Diaspora
here in the US, in Africa,

00:05:04.180 --> 00:05:06.110
in the Caribbean, wherever.

00:05:06.110 --> 00:05:09.110
And books about history,
politics, culture,

00:05:09.110 --> 00:05:10.980
intellectual discourse,
whatever.

00:05:10.980 --> 00:05:14.320
So he pulled the
titles as we requested,

00:05:14.320 --> 00:05:17.170
but then he pulled a lot more.

00:05:17.170 --> 00:05:20.840
He also showed us a
few black kids books,

00:05:20.840 --> 00:05:25.440
mainly African folktales and
a few others, but just a few.

00:05:25.440 --> 00:05:27.740
Because this is 1968.

00:05:27.740 --> 00:05:31.310
So we didn't yet have the
federal mandate that required

00:05:31.310 --> 00:05:34.800
that children's books used
in schools reflect the makeup

00:05:34.800 --> 00:05:37.270
of the children in the
communities that they served.

00:05:37.270 --> 00:05:38.860
That had not happened yet.

00:05:38.860 --> 00:05:42.380
So we got more books, we
stained the bookshelves

00:05:42.380 --> 00:05:44.830
and we opened the store.

00:05:44.830 --> 00:05:48.790
Purposely, we wanted it on
14th Street, but I'm going

00:05:48.790 --> 00:05:51.490
to let Tony and Jennifer and
Courtland talk about that,

00:05:51.490 --> 00:05:53.590
about the politics
of the location,

00:05:53.590 --> 00:05:55.820
why they decided
to start the store.

00:05:55.820 --> 00:05:59.160
I will say what I did understand
even first coming in was

00:05:59.160 --> 00:06:01.480
that Charlie Cobb had
initially had the idea

00:06:01.480 --> 00:06:03.120
from going through Vietnam.

00:06:03.120 --> 00:06:04.760
And that's a whole other
story which I won't take

00:06:04.760 --> 00:06:06.750
up my seven minutes
to tell you about.

00:06:06.750 --> 00:06:10.280
But he sees this idea,
he comes through Paris.

00:06:10.280 --> 00:06:13.320
He sees it in Paris,
sees the cafÃ©, sees books

00:06:13.320 --> 00:06:15.590
and people having
coffee and discoursing.

00:06:15.590 --> 00:06:17.720
And he thinks, "Oh,
I can do that in DC."

00:06:17.720 --> 00:06:21.750
Now it helps him that his
father was the founder

00:06:21.750 --> 00:06:25.050
and then 15 years into
being the executive director

00:06:25.050 --> 00:06:28.710
of the United Church of Christ
Commission for Racial Justice.

00:06:28.710 --> 00:06:30.010
So he had money.

00:06:30.010 --> 00:06:32.660
So he gives us the
first $10,000.

00:06:32.660 --> 00:06:35.730
Hey. So we are set at least
for the first $10,000.

00:06:35.730 --> 00:06:40.570
We also have the Episcopal
church at 815 Second Avenue.

00:06:40.570 --> 00:06:44.030
They used to give
us money as well.

00:06:44.030 --> 00:06:50.650
Okay, so the basic point is that
we sited the store deliberately

00:06:50.650 --> 00:06:53.400
at 14th and Fairmont
because it was in the heart

00:06:53.400 --> 00:06:55.410
of the black community.

00:06:55.410 --> 00:06:58.700
And understanding to that this
was an economically depressed

00:06:58.700 --> 00:07:00.000
section of DC.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:01.710
This was not the
Gold Coast, right?

00:07:01.710 --> 00:07:05.110
But it was a section of
high energy and culture.

00:07:05.110 --> 00:07:06.410
There was a jazz place

00:07:06.410 --> 00:07:08.200
that I can't remember the
name of up the street.

00:07:08.200 --> 00:07:10.530
There was just lots going on.

00:07:10.530 --> 00:07:14.070
And it was just such high
cultural and political energy

00:07:14.070 --> 00:07:17.670
in DC at that time, it
really was chocolate city.

00:07:17.670 --> 00:07:22.300
So we are able to
bounce off of all

00:07:22.300 --> 00:07:24.620
of that energy in
doing our store.

00:07:24.620 --> 00:07:26.140
Now I was going to
ask Tony to do this,

00:07:26.140 --> 00:07:27.660
but he doesn't really
remember it, so I'm going

00:07:27.660 --> 00:07:29.830
to tell the story anyway, okay?

00:07:29.830 --> 00:07:33.530
So we were selling not
only to individuals in DC,

00:07:33.530 --> 00:07:39.420
but also institutionally to the
new black studies departments

00:07:39.420 --> 00:07:40.720
that had been fueled

00:07:40.720 --> 00:07:44.040
by the Toward the Black
University Conference that comes

00:07:44.040 --> 00:07:46.030
out of the takeover
that Tony was one

00:07:46.030 --> 00:07:47.580
of the two main leaders for.

00:07:47.580 --> 00:07:49.950
So that had just
happened in 1968,

00:07:49.950 --> 00:07:52.750
take over the administration
building at Howard, right?

00:07:52.750 --> 00:07:54.140
I see Tony at the bookstore.

00:07:54.140 --> 00:07:56.610
I don't even know that
he's just come off that.

00:07:56.610 --> 00:07:59.830
What I do know is that in '69,

00:07:59.830 --> 00:08:02.320
because of the Toward the
Black University Conference

00:08:02.320 --> 00:08:04.570
that gets fueled
by the takeover --

00:08:04.570 --> 00:08:05.870
because that's one
of the demands

00:08:05.870 --> 00:08:08.010
and they get a Toward the
Black University Conference --

00:08:08.010 --> 00:08:11.460
you get black studies
departments.

00:08:11.460 --> 00:08:12.930
No, programs.

00:08:12.930 --> 00:08:15.130
They rarely become departments.

00:08:15.130 --> 00:08:21.000
Black studies programs at San
Francisco State, at Cornell,

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:22.420
at a lot of these universities.

00:08:22.420 --> 00:08:24.820
So they're institutionally
buying books

00:08:24.820 --> 00:08:26.480
from Drum and Spear Bookstore.

00:08:26.480 --> 00:08:30.670
That's really helpful.

00:08:30.670 --> 00:08:33.950
I should also say that what
the Bookazine staffer started

00:08:33.950 --> 00:08:36.830
in terms of children's
books we ran with.

00:08:36.830 --> 00:08:39.550
So we built what
became a wonderful

00:08:39.550 --> 00:08:42.380
and extensive children's
section of black books.

00:08:42.380 --> 00:08:45.750
Picture books, young adult
books, comic books, et cetera.

00:08:45.750 --> 00:08:48.420
And we were able to
include Eloise Greenfield,

00:08:48.420 --> 00:08:52.520
Sharon Bell Mathis, DC authors,
as well as Lucille Clifton

00:08:52.520 --> 00:08:55.260
from Baltimore and
so many others.

00:08:55.260 --> 00:08:58.230
In fact, we became a magnet
for some black teachers

00:08:58.230 --> 00:08:59.830
who normally did
not come up into

00:08:59.830 --> 00:09:02.250
that portion of 14th Street.

00:09:02.250 --> 00:09:04.980
And they would often
be amazed to find all

00:09:04.980 --> 00:09:08.920
of the children's books that had
black and Latino children in it.

00:09:08.920 --> 00:09:14.000
Because they had not
formerly been exposed to that.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:21.520
And that has to do with
who wrote the books

00:09:21.520 --> 00:09:22.830
and whom they were sold to.

00:09:22.830 --> 00:09:25.480
And we can go into that
at some other point.

00:09:25.480 --> 00:09:27.610
At that point you
had Brent Hanos

00:09:27.610 --> 00:09:29.890
and that was then
the chain down town.

00:09:29.890 --> 00:09:32.050
But it really wasn't
carrying black books,

00:09:32.050 --> 00:09:33.870
adult or children's.

00:09:33.870 --> 00:09:37.210
And in fact, our
experience starting Drum

00:09:37.210 --> 00:09:38.940
and Spear Bookstore seemed

00:09:38.940 --> 00:09:42.400
to really surprise both
the mainstream bookstores

00:09:42.400 --> 00:09:44.190
and the publishers to find

00:09:44.190 --> 00:09:46.360
out that black people
really read books.

00:09:46.360 --> 00:09:49.150
What a concept, right?

00:09:49.150 --> 00:09:52.780
And they started doing
books at a lower price

00:09:52.780 --> 00:09:57.000
but never the extensive
stock that we had

00:09:57.000 --> 00:09:59.730
in both children's books
and adult books and --

00:09:59.730 --> 00:10:02.460
oh gosh, African
literary services.

00:10:02.460 --> 00:10:06.360
We had so much from the African
diaspora around the world.

00:10:06.360 --> 00:10:09.830
Now we also ended up --
and in fact, by the way,

00:10:09.830 --> 00:10:13.900
the children's section
with history and literature

00:10:13.900 --> 00:10:16.010
for all ages becomes one

00:10:16.010 --> 00:10:19.040
of the most popular
sections of the store.

00:10:19.040 --> 00:10:20.780
And I know Debra Mancart who was
head of Teaching for Change --

00:10:20.780 --> 00:10:23.830
and everybody should go
grab her at the end of this.

00:10:23.830 --> 00:10:29.980
She had the bookstore
at Busboy's and Towitz.

00:10:29.980 --> 00:10:31.280
Not Towitz.

00:10:31.280 --> 00:10:34.610
Busboys and Poets at
14th Street, initially.

00:10:34.610 --> 00:10:37.340
And is still so active
and has what,

00:10:37.340 --> 00:10:40.950
84,000 teachers nationwide
on their list.

00:10:40.950 --> 00:10:43.140
This is the lady, okay?

00:10:43.140 --> 00:10:47.430
So in a lot of ways, what we
were learning is the importance

00:10:47.430 --> 00:10:49.390
of children's books
to bring in people.

00:10:49.390 --> 00:10:51.050
And that's something
we knew in SNCC.

00:10:51.050 --> 00:10:52.350
This is obscure.

00:10:52.350 --> 00:10:53.650
Something we knew in SNCC,

00:10:53.650 --> 00:10:55.860
because one of the ways
we organized SNCC is

00:10:55.860 --> 00:10:58.670
that you started freedom schools
and you did things with children

00:10:58.670 --> 00:11:00.880
because it brought
the parents in.

00:11:00.880 --> 00:11:02.770
And then they would
get registered to vote.

00:11:02.770 --> 00:11:04.440
We understood the
importance of children.

00:11:04.440 --> 00:11:08.440
Okay, so we ended up doing a
number of teachers conferences

00:11:08.440 --> 00:11:11.060
and exhibits in DC
and out of town.

00:11:11.060 --> 00:11:13.830
And we often made more
in a one-day exhibit

00:11:13.830 --> 00:11:16.470
than we sometimes made
in a week in the store.

00:11:16.470 --> 00:11:18.730
So Drum and Spear Press,

00:11:18.730 --> 00:11:20.640
brings me to how we
published the first book

00:11:20.640 --> 00:11:23.840
of now-famous children's book
author Eloise Greenfield,

00:11:23.840 --> 00:11:25.140
Bubbles.

00:11:25.140 --> 00:11:26.440
She's a DC native.

00:11:26.440 --> 00:11:29.660
She still lives and
writes here in DC.

00:11:29.660 --> 00:11:32.440
Oh, they want me to slow down.

00:11:32.440 --> 00:11:34.070
Oh no, he's telling me
I've got tow minutes.

00:11:34.070 --> 00:11:36.030
That's why I'm talking
so quickly.

00:11:36.030 --> 00:11:38.040
[ Laughter ]

00:11:38.040 --> 00:11:40.690
Okay, so we had formed
Drum and Spear Press.

00:11:40.690 --> 00:11:44.290
We had our office in the
Roundstone and Amos Morgan

00:11:44.290 --> 00:11:47.580
at 18th and Belmont,
all three floors.

00:11:47.580 --> 00:11:51.630
And only one other black
publisher then existed,

00:11:51.630 --> 00:11:53.220
and that was of nonfiction
books,

00:11:53.220 --> 00:11:55.830
and that was Dudley
Randal who had Broadside.

00:11:55.830 --> 00:11:57.320
But he mainly did poetry.

00:11:57.320 --> 00:12:01.050
So Eloise Greenfield
hadn't yet published.

00:12:01.050 --> 00:12:03.190
And she sent us her manuscript,

00:12:03.190 --> 00:12:05.160
what becomes her
first book, Bubbles.

00:12:05.160 --> 00:12:07.330
I was the children's
book editor.

00:12:07.330 --> 00:12:10.930
I remember now these
folks, Charlie and Courtland

00:12:10.930 --> 00:12:13.820
and Jennifer were away
in Tanzania doing Drum

00:12:13.820 --> 00:12:15.630
and Spear Press East Africa.

00:12:15.630 --> 00:12:18.500
So I'm up there.

00:12:18.500 --> 00:12:19.800
We had no money.

00:12:19.800 --> 00:12:21.100
So we had no fuel.

00:12:21.100 --> 00:12:22.400
So I was freezing.

00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:23.780
I remember being in a coat.

00:12:23.780 --> 00:12:26.560
Jimmy the rat had the kitchen
and I had a sign that said,

00:12:26.560 --> 00:12:29.100
Jimmy the rat has the
kitchen; go in at your peril.

00:12:29.100 --> 00:12:32.730
And I'm reading these
manuscripts.

00:12:32.730 --> 00:12:35.420
And I find this one from
Eloise Greenfield and it is

00:12:35.420 --> 00:12:36.720
such a wonderful story.

00:12:36.720 --> 00:12:39.710
I call her that night and I
said, "I'm calling from Drum

00:12:39.710 --> 00:12:42.210
and Spear Press and we
want to do your book."

00:12:42.210 --> 00:12:44.040
Now this is the book
that we did.

00:12:44.040 --> 00:12:45.340
It was called Bubbles.

00:12:45.340 --> 00:12:46.640
Oh, it was so wonderful.

00:12:46.640 --> 00:12:47.940
It had all these illustrations.

00:12:47.940 --> 00:12:50.800
Okay. So natural extension, I'm
going quickly, natural extension

00:12:50.800 --> 00:12:52.840
from our interest in
children's literature is

00:12:52.840 --> 00:12:55.530
to our radio program,
Sia Watoto.

00:12:55.530 --> 00:13:01.420
So Dewey Hughes was the program
director at WOL here in DC.

00:13:01.420 --> 00:13:05.490
And he offered us time for
a weekly children's program.

00:13:05.490 --> 00:13:09.400
I became BB Amina and
I was the host, right?

00:13:09.400 --> 00:13:13.030
So I opened it saying, "Jumbo,
my young brothers and sisters.

00:13:13.030 --> 00:13:15.730
This is BB Amina
bringing you Sia Watoto,

00:13:15.730 --> 00:13:18.470
which is The Children's Hour

00:13:18.470 --> 00:13:20.280
in the African language
of Swahili."

00:13:20.280 --> 00:13:21.580
I knew no Swahili.

00:13:21.580 --> 00:13:23.930
I learned how to say Sia
Watoto from Jennifer.

00:13:23.930 --> 00:13:27.330
Okay, and so all these
children would plug in

00:13:27.330 --> 00:13:28.630
and their parents would plug in.

00:13:28.630 --> 00:13:31.540
So Mimi Hayes and I,
another SNCC person,

00:13:31.540 --> 00:13:34.890
developed the scripts
from African folktales.

00:13:34.890 --> 00:13:38.530
Jennifer, Tony, Courtland,
others, all became characters

00:13:38.530 --> 00:13:41.950
in our taping of
these folktales.

00:13:41.950 --> 00:13:44.430
So they were Mr. Rabbit
and Miss Elephant.

00:13:44.430 --> 00:13:48.810
And drumming was provided by
Topper Carew's New Thing Art

00:13:48.810 --> 00:13:51.650
and Architecture Center
which was down 18th street.

00:13:51.650 --> 00:13:55.690
And this was a black-oriented
arts organization.

00:13:55.690 --> 00:13:57.960
And so one of their
guys would drum

00:13:57.960 --> 00:14:01.100
and he would provide the
music while we did Sia Watoto.

00:14:01.100 --> 00:14:04.520
I also did visits as BB Amina
in African dress and the gala

00:14:04.520 --> 00:14:06.670
and I'm reading from
the children's book.

00:14:06.670 --> 00:14:09.310
Then, and this is the end,
we had Malazo Bookstore.

00:14:09.310 --> 00:14:13.140
So black employees of what
was then the HEW building

00:14:13.140 --> 00:14:17.180
that becomes HHS, they
wanted a satellite.

00:14:17.180 --> 00:14:20.780
They were offered a store
in the HEW building.

00:14:20.780 --> 00:14:23.630
Elliot Richardson, then the
director of HEW, said, "Oh,

00:14:23.630 --> 00:14:26.680
they'll probably want
a clothing store."

00:14:26.680 --> 00:14:29.750
No, they wanted a satellite
of Drum and Spear Bookstore.

00:14:29.750 --> 00:14:33.680
So we then -- I organized
this new bookstore,

00:14:33.680 --> 00:14:35.170
again going to Jennifer.

00:14:35.170 --> 00:14:37.660
"What is a name for a
store that has books?"

00:14:37.660 --> 00:14:41.650
So we came up with Malazo, which
of course nobody could find

00:14:41.650 --> 00:14:43.060
because you know,
this is before Google,

00:14:43.060 --> 00:14:44.880
and how would you
remember Malazo?

00:14:44.880 --> 00:14:47.210
Anyway, so we started the store

00:14:47.210 --> 00:14:52.000
and it became really a
wonderful area where a lot

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:54.340
of the black employees and
white employees could find

00:14:54.340 --> 00:14:57.540
out about all this
literature about black people.

00:14:57.540 --> 00:15:02.800
Now, last story is I'm
sitting there and somebody,

00:15:02.800 --> 00:15:06.170
a salesperson from
Scholastic Books comes in.

00:15:06.170 --> 00:15:11.290
Now Scholastic was then and is
still now the largest publisher

00:15:11.290 --> 00:15:12.980
of children's books, right?

00:15:12.980 --> 00:15:19.510
Oh, okay, I thought
-- okay, fine.

00:15:19.510 --> 00:15:22.040
[ Laughter ]

00:15:22.040 --> 00:15:25.740
This is my last story.

00:15:25.740 --> 00:15:29.170
So he comes in, Scholastic
books, and he opens his --

00:15:29.170 --> 00:15:31.450
now by the way, there are
African masks all over.

00:15:31.450 --> 00:15:33.030
I'm in a gala, okay?

00:15:33.030 --> 00:15:36.790
And he opens his catalog,
you know, his book,

00:15:36.790 --> 00:15:38.960
and it's all white books.

00:15:38.960 --> 00:15:41.680
And so I said, "But
what about" --

00:15:41.680 --> 00:15:44.170
it was one of my
favorite children's books,

00:15:44.170 --> 00:15:45.470
Sunflowers for Tina.

00:15:45.470 --> 00:15:48.850
And I said, "Oh, but what
about Sunflowers for Tina?"

00:15:48.850 --> 00:15:52.580
And he says, "Oh, I didn't know
this was a black bookstore."

00:15:52.580 --> 00:15:55.210
Now, what that meant is like --

00:15:55.210 --> 00:15:57.940
okay, you're only going to
sell these black-oriented books

00:15:57.940 --> 00:15:59.310
to the black bookstores.

00:15:59.310 --> 00:16:01.310
And so the white
folks and Latino folks

00:16:01.310 --> 00:16:03.270
and anybody else is not
going to have the benefit

00:16:03.270 --> 00:16:06.380
of these wonderful stories,
not to mention the fact

00:16:06.380 --> 00:16:07.680
that black kids will not be able

00:16:07.680 --> 00:16:08.980
to see themselves
in these stories.

00:16:08.980 --> 00:16:13.200
So luckily, some of
that has changed,

00:16:13.200 --> 00:16:16.180
but Debra knows how
difficult the road still is.

00:16:16.180 --> 00:16:19.770
And so I'm going to stop there
and that goes over to you, Tony.

00:16:19.770 --> 00:16:22.500
&gt;&gt; Guha Shenkar:
Thank you, thank you.

00:16:22.500 --> 00:16:24.790
Tony?

00:16:24.790 --> 00:16:26.410
&gt;&gt; Tony Gittens: When we were
doing all this, and Judy,

00:16:26.410 --> 00:16:28.780
I forgot half of this
stuff and how we met.

00:16:28.780 --> 00:16:31.040
But when we were doing all this,
you've got to think we were

00:16:31.040 --> 00:16:35.050
like 25, 26, you know, we
thought we could do anything.

00:16:35.050 --> 00:16:36.760
We thought we could do anything.

00:16:36.760 --> 00:16:43.340
And when I met Charlie,
Courtland and some other folks

00:16:43.340 --> 00:16:47.360
from SNCC and Judy, back in '68,

00:16:47.360 --> 00:16:49.590
as Judy mentioned I had
just come out of Howard

00:16:49.590 --> 00:16:53.950
with no real plan to do
anything else after that.

00:16:53.950 --> 00:16:55.250
What to do, I don't know.

00:16:55.250 --> 00:16:57.540
I just knew I wasn't
going into the army.

00:16:57.540 --> 00:16:59.170
We took care of that.

00:16:59.170 --> 00:17:02.320
But then I remember being
up at Charlie's apartment

00:17:02.320 --> 00:17:04.860
and Charlie talking
about the bookstore.

00:17:04.860 --> 00:17:07.610
And saying, "You know,
we really need a manager

00:17:07.610 --> 00:17:08.910
for the bookstore."

00:17:08.910 --> 00:17:10.420
So I said, "You know,
I'll do it."

00:17:10.420 --> 00:17:13.310
And I remember Charlie
throwing me the keys --

00:17:13.310 --> 00:17:16.280
throwing me the keys and sort
of leaving me to figure out what

00:17:16.280 --> 00:17:18.640
to do next with a lot of help.

00:17:18.640 --> 00:17:21.200
So that's how I got
involved with Drum and Spear.

00:17:21.200 --> 00:17:22.500
I was the first manager.

00:17:22.500 --> 00:17:24.840
I think I did it
for about a year

00:17:24.840 --> 00:17:28.820
until Ralph Featherstone
took over.

00:17:28.820 --> 00:17:36.310
But when folks asked that
we talk about the past,

00:17:36.310 --> 00:17:43.020
I try to do my best to be as
honest about is as possible.

00:17:43.020 --> 00:17:47.710
Why? Because they're young
people who are involved

00:17:47.710 --> 00:17:52.800
in organizing, setting
up institutions and such.

00:17:52.800 --> 00:17:58.420
And sometimes folks can get
taken away by the romance

00:17:58.420 --> 00:18:02.290
of what happened
in '68 and earlier.

00:18:02.290 --> 00:18:07.560
And so I'm here to break up all
that romance to give them --

00:18:07.560 --> 00:18:09.590
I mean really to
give folks some sense

00:18:09.590 --> 00:18:14.020
of when things don't go the
way you want them to go.

00:18:14.020 --> 00:18:16.170
That you're not doing
anything wrong.

00:18:16.170 --> 00:18:17.470
It's the nature of it.

00:18:17.470 --> 00:18:18.860
You're pushing against
the culture.

00:18:18.860 --> 00:18:21.460
You're pushing against in
our case a lot of folks

00:18:21.460 --> 00:18:26.290
who have were so much more
powerful than we were.

00:18:26.290 --> 00:18:28.670
And sometimes things
didn't work out.

00:18:28.670 --> 00:18:33.370
So I really appreciate so
much of what Judy had to say

00:18:33.370 --> 00:18:35.320
because I just really
didn't recall it.

00:18:35.320 --> 00:18:38.440
My recollection of drum
and spear was hard work.

00:18:38.440 --> 00:18:43.280
My recollection was
sometimes, most of the time,

00:18:43.280 --> 00:18:46.630
seven days a week, long hours.

00:18:46.630 --> 00:18:50.380
Not only me, but the other
folks who were working on it,

00:18:50.380 --> 00:18:56.060
Jennifer, Courtland, Judy, that
it was long, it was hard work.

00:18:56.060 --> 00:18:57.980
And that's my recollection
of it.

00:18:57.980 --> 00:18:59.280
There were high points [laughs],

00:18:59.280 --> 00:19:03.880
but somehow they don't
come immediately to mind,

00:19:03.880 --> 00:19:06.690
at least they're not visceral.

00:19:06.690 --> 00:19:07.990
[Laughs] You know,
the other folks

00:19:07.990 --> 00:19:09.660
on the panel I'm sure
will talk about them.

00:19:09.660 --> 00:19:12.220
So I was trying to think
about a way to sort of present

00:19:12.220 --> 00:19:13.950
at least my point of view on it.

00:19:13.950 --> 00:19:16.630
And I think the best way for me

00:19:16.630 --> 00:19:18.900
to do it is like,
"What did we learn?

00:19:18.900 --> 00:19:22.200
What have we learned from
going through that experience?"

00:19:22.200 --> 00:19:24.750
And so I think one
thing we learned --

00:19:24.750 --> 00:19:28.860
we sort of knew this going
in -- is that racism lives in

00:19:28.860 --> 00:19:30.940
and is maintained
by institutions.

00:19:30.940 --> 00:19:35.020
That can only be combated by
building counter institutions.

00:19:35.020 --> 00:19:38.410
And the folks at African
American Resources,

00:19:38.410 --> 00:19:39.780
Courtland can talk I'm sure more

00:19:39.780 --> 00:19:42.150
about this, and I
was part of it.

00:19:42.150 --> 00:19:44.930
I was on the board,
had some say,

00:19:44.930 --> 00:19:49.220
even though I just
got out of school.

00:19:49.220 --> 00:19:51.760
The idea was to build
an institution

00:19:51.760 --> 00:19:56.330
that would counteract
the racist information.

00:19:56.330 --> 00:20:00.850
And we wanted to build
educational institutions

00:20:00.850 --> 00:20:03.360
that were communication
institutions.

00:20:03.360 --> 00:20:07.740
And so we had the bookstores.

00:20:07.740 --> 00:20:09.670
We had two bookstores to present

00:20:09.670 --> 00:20:12.990
that information
in written form.

00:20:12.990 --> 00:20:15.250
We also had the press
which Judy mentioned,

00:20:15.250 --> 00:20:18.440
and folks down the way will
talk about that a bit more.

00:20:18.440 --> 00:20:21.340
And we had the children's
show which I had forgotten.

00:20:21.340 --> 00:20:22.950
The other person
who was a character

00:20:22.950 --> 00:20:24.370
on that show was Kojo Nnambi.

00:20:24.370 --> 00:20:25.670
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: Yes.

00:20:25.670 --> 00:20:30.250
&gt;&gt; Tony Gittens: We would gather
up in that studio once a week.

00:20:30.250 --> 00:20:31.550
Who wrote the script?

00:20:31.550 --> 00:20:32.850
Mimi wrote the script.

00:20:32.850 --> 00:20:34.150
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson:
Yeah, that's right.

00:20:34.150 --> 00:20:35.450
&gt;&gt; Tony Gittens: Mimi
wrote the scripts

00:20:35.450 --> 00:20:36.750
and we would read these things
cold and sort of make it

00:20:36.750 --> 00:20:38.270
up almost as we were
going along.

00:20:38.270 --> 00:20:40.890
It was great fun.

00:20:40.890 --> 00:20:42.830
I remember that as a highlight.

00:20:42.830 --> 00:20:44.560
And we had a school.

00:20:44.560 --> 00:20:49.270
And we had all of
these satellite things

00:20:49.270 --> 00:20:52.840
around African American
resources that were attempts

00:20:52.840 --> 00:20:54.530
to build an institution

00:20:54.530 --> 00:20:57.520
to counteract all the other
information, negative,

00:20:57.520 --> 00:21:00.360
racist information that
was being put forth

00:21:00.360 --> 00:21:02.860
by the larger society.

00:21:02.860 --> 00:21:06.290
And so that was very
intentional, very purposeful.

00:21:06.290 --> 00:21:07.590
That's why we did it.

00:21:07.590 --> 00:21:09.340
What we learned is you've got
to have that kind of focus

00:21:09.340 --> 00:21:11.820
or you're just going to
be floating out there.

00:21:11.820 --> 00:21:15.370
Any old idea that would pop up,
you would be attracted to it,

00:21:15.370 --> 00:21:18.440
but it wasn't in keeping, it
wasn't viable in some way.

00:21:18.440 --> 00:21:21.340
It was passed on.

00:21:21.340 --> 00:21:25.320
We learned that there are
unavoidable contradictions

00:21:25.320 --> 00:21:27.960
in conducting a capitalist
enterprise like Drum

00:21:27.960 --> 00:21:32.260
and Spear while we practice
progressive politics

00:21:32.260 --> 00:21:35.170
that oppose capitalist
enterprises.

00:21:35.170 --> 00:21:36.780
In other words, we were --

00:21:36.780 --> 00:21:40.120
and Josh does a great job in
his book which I would refer

00:21:40.120 --> 00:21:42.080
to anybody who's
here and interested

00:21:42.080 --> 00:21:44.070
in this subject at all.

00:21:44.070 --> 00:21:46.930
He does a great job
about describing not only

00:21:46.930 --> 00:21:50.080
in our case -- get out of here.

00:21:50.080 --> 00:21:52.150
[ Laughter ]

00:21:52.150 --> 00:21:55.030
I'm only up to two.

00:21:55.030 --> 00:22:00.100
[Laughs] Okay, I'll speak more
quickly and more concisely.

00:22:00.100 --> 00:22:04.060
So Josh does a great description

00:22:04.060 --> 00:22:07.310
and real hard-hitting
description about not only

00:22:07.310 --> 00:22:10.590
in our case and in the case
of other black bookstores,

00:22:10.590 --> 00:22:15.250
but other what he calls
activist enterprises that went

00:22:15.250 --> 00:22:16.550
through the same thing.

00:22:16.550 --> 00:22:19.480
So I'm just going to
read one quote from him.

00:22:19.480 --> 00:22:24.840
Josh puts it in his excellent
book, "Activist entrepreneurs

00:22:24.840 --> 00:22:28.010
who criticize capitalism could
not totally ignore economic

00:22:28.010 --> 00:22:30.840
realities if they
wanted their enterprise

00:22:30.840 --> 00:22:33.300
to survive in the long-term.

00:22:33.300 --> 00:22:34.940
Indeed, the greatest threat

00:22:34.940 --> 00:22:39.530
to activist entrepreneurs
was not being co-opted,

00:22:39.530 --> 00:22:41.740
but simply going
out of business.

00:22:41.740 --> 00:22:44.690
Many activist enterprises
stayed in business

00:22:44.690 --> 00:22:47.850
for only a few years, and
most of those that emerged

00:22:47.850 --> 00:22:53.310
in the 1960's and 1970's did
not make it into the '80's."

00:22:53.310 --> 00:22:57.190
One other point about that,
that when I became manager

00:22:57.190 --> 00:22:59.400
of the bookstore,
I went to New York.

00:22:59.400 --> 00:23:02.110
I went to Michaux's bookstore
which was the iconic,

00:23:02.110 --> 00:23:06.280
the granddaddy of all the black
bookstores in the country.

00:23:06.280 --> 00:23:09.030
And I had an opportunity
to talk to its owner

00:23:09.030 --> 00:23:11.310
and founder Lewis Michaux.

00:23:11.310 --> 00:23:15.910
And when I talked to him, what
we talked about, I said, "Look,

00:23:15.910 --> 00:23:17.880
man, I'm trying to figure
out how to do this."

00:23:17.880 --> 00:23:20.350
And he gave me some advice.

00:23:20.350 --> 00:23:22.330
And he said, "Always
remember that you've got

00:23:22.330 --> 00:23:25.680
to pay the sales
tax every quarter.

00:23:25.680 --> 00:23:29.180
Never overbuy, overstock
the bookstore.

00:23:29.180 --> 00:23:31.080
Don't take on too much credit."

00:23:31.080 --> 00:23:33.040
We didn't talk about
one of the books

00:23:33.040 --> 00:23:34.880
that he had on his shelves.

00:23:34.880 --> 00:23:38.720
The intellectual discourse
was somebody else's concern.

00:23:38.720 --> 00:23:40.390
But he knew, and
I learned a lot,

00:23:40.390 --> 00:23:43.750
I mean just in the time
I was speaking with him,

00:23:43.750 --> 00:23:45.540
about what to do
and what to avoid.

00:23:45.540 --> 00:23:48.330
And so that was my
approach to it.

00:23:48.330 --> 00:23:49.630
Number three, I'll be quick.

00:23:49.630 --> 00:23:53.470
From the very beginning, we
learned that Drum and Spear was

00:23:53.470 --> 00:23:55.630
about more than selling books.

00:23:55.630 --> 00:24:00.360
That my job was not just
making the trains run on time,

00:24:00.360 --> 00:24:04.740
but the store had become this
community gathering place

00:24:04.740 --> 00:24:07.690
that folks would come
in to talk, to meet.

00:24:07.690 --> 00:24:10.820
A lot of the things that the
programs that Judy had done,

00:24:10.820 --> 00:24:13.270
and then Courtland and Jennifer
had done others and other people

00:24:13.270 --> 00:24:16.700
in our staff had done -- you
know, all of that was expected

00:24:16.700 --> 00:24:18.500
to happen in the bookstore.

00:24:18.500 --> 00:24:23.790
So we had a responsibility
to not only sell books,

00:24:23.790 --> 00:24:27.940
but also to serve the
community in other ways.

00:24:27.940 --> 00:24:31.160
We learned that building
an enterprise like Drum

00:24:31.160 --> 00:24:33.890
and Spear is continuous
hard work, as I mentioned.

00:24:33.890 --> 00:24:36.900
It requires long hours
and often days and weeks.

00:24:36.900 --> 00:24:40.880
It also included cantankerous
disagreements among ourselves.

00:24:40.880 --> 00:24:45.600
Good intentions for the struggle
do not eliminate hard-headed

00:24:45.600 --> 00:24:46.950
human nature.

00:24:46.950 --> 00:24:48.790
We had arguments among ourselves

00:24:48.790 --> 00:24:51.500
and pretty much we
kept it to ourselves.

00:24:51.500 --> 00:24:53.570
That just comes with it,
you guys who are planning

00:24:53.570 --> 00:24:56.240
to do a similar kind of project.

00:24:56.240 --> 00:24:57.800
You're not doing anything wrong.

00:24:57.800 --> 00:25:00.760
And finally we learned that
our success would help lead

00:25:00.760 --> 00:25:03.260
to our own demise,
as Judy pointed out.

00:25:03.260 --> 00:25:07.900
Drum and Spear showed that there
was a market for black books.

00:25:07.900 --> 00:25:13.620
And the bigger bookstores like
Brintano's and Barnes and Noble,

00:25:13.620 --> 00:25:17.950
they also saw that and they
began to take our customers.

00:25:17.950 --> 00:25:21.920
They might have been
limited, as Judy pointed out,

00:25:21.920 --> 00:25:24.040
to just a section
in their bookstore.

00:25:24.040 --> 00:25:25.810
But they were selling books

00:25:25.810 --> 00:25:29.210
that they never would have
touched before we showed

00:25:29.210 --> 00:25:30.550
that it was possible.

00:25:30.550 --> 00:25:36.320
They did book parties and book
signings for black authors

00:25:36.320 --> 00:25:39.550
that they never would have
bothered with until we showed

00:25:39.550 --> 00:25:41.350
that we had a line
around the corner coming

00:25:41.350 --> 00:25:44.660
in to see Eloise Greenfield
and people like that.

00:25:44.660 --> 00:25:47.220
Julius Lester.

00:25:47.220 --> 00:25:52.720
That we showed that
that was possible.

00:25:52.720 --> 00:25:56.980
And like all good capitalists,
they took from us and went on.

00:25:56.980 --> 00:25:59.460
And then that as true.

00:25:59.460 --> 00:26:02.260
I mean, if we were running a
pure capitalist enterprise,

00:26:02.260 --> 00:26:05.690
what capitalists do is they
take, or so I understand,

00:26:05.690 --> 00:26:08.580
they take that money and they
put it back into the business.

00:26:08.580 --> 00:26:11.440
Any profits we had,
any excess cash we put

00:26:11.440 --> 00:26:13.540
into our activist activities.

00:26:13.540 --> 00:26:15.870
And then towards
the end, you know,

00:26:15.870 --> 00:26:19.760
it wasn't possible
for us to do both.

00:26:19.760 --> 00:26:21.320
We couldn't do both.

00:26:21.320 --> 00:26:24.140
You know, it was too
late to be practical

00:26:24.140 --> 00:26:28.240
because we found ourselves in a
financial hole and other things.

00:26:28.240 --> 00:26:30.210
Josh talks about what happened.

00:26:30.210 --> 00:26:33.570
When you relate it to a
movement, then that interest

00:26:33.570 --> 00:26:35.730
in the movement will
help people come

00:26:35.730 --> 00:26:37.820
and help fund your enterprise.

00:26:37.820 --> 00:26:42.340
When the movement becomes not as
prominent, then people go away

00:26:42.340 --> 00:26:46.280
or move on to something else,
then you don't have those people

00:26:46.280 --> 00:26:52.880
who will come, and over time
you begin to fall apart,

00:26:52.880 --> 00:26:54.980
which is what happened to us.

00:26:54.980 --> 00:26:57.520
So I can go more into it,
but I've got to move on.

00:26:57.520 --> 00:26:59.290
Thank you.

00:26:59.290 --> 00:27:01.620
&gt;&gt; Guha Shenkar: So Courtland
is going to be up next.

00:27:01.620 --> 00:27:04.150
Thank you.

00:27:04.150 --> 00:27:08.880
&gt;&gt; Courtland Cox: All right,
well Tony and Judy talked

00:27:08.880 --> 00:27:13.860
about what we did
and how we did it.

00:27:13.860 --> 00:27:18.040
I'd like to spend a few minutes
talking about why we did it.

00:27:18.040 --> 00:27:27.000
The reason we did it was that
it was important to be able

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:31.460
to have the power to define.

00:27:31.460 --> 00:27:37.700
When we were coming along in
the '60's, one of the things

00:27:37.700 --> 00:27:46.950
that we faced was a
narrative that said

00:27:46.950 --> 00:27:51.240
that Africans contributed
nothing to civilization,

00:27:51.240 --> 00:27:55.820
they have never done anything
and they will never do anything.

00:27:55.820 --> 00:28:01.080
And the sense of the
narrative of superiority

00:28:01.080 --> 00:28:08.850
and inferiority was built
on a whole discussion

00:28:08.850 --> 00:28:12.100
about our lack of contribution.

00:28:12.100 --> 00:28:20.000
And that existed you know,
both in Ivy League colleges

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:26.340
and existed in a
number of institutions.

00:28:26.340 --> 00:28:31.540
But unfortunately, it also
existed in our communities.

00:28:31.540 --> 00:28:37.730
And that one of the things that
was particularly important was

00:28:37.730 --> 00:28:42.360
to be able to create a
definition of ourselves

00:28:42.360 --> 00:28:47.490
that we could control and
that we would be proud of.

00:28:47.490 --> 00:28:52.830
And I remember -- and it's
just a very simple thing --

00:28:52.830 --> 00:28:58.570
if you call somebody black in
1960, it was a high insult.

00:28:58.570 --> 00:29:02.120
If you call them a negro
today, it's an insult.

00:29:02.120 --> 00:29:07.190
So the ability to define
was particularly important.

00:29:08.780 --> 00:29:15.700
I think that probably when we
looked at it, there were two

00:29:15.700 --> 00:29:21.260
or three lonely souls,
Carnegie Woodson, J. A. Rogers

00:29:21.260 --> 00:29:25.190
and a couple of others,
who tried to talk

00:29:25.190 --> 00:29:28.920
about the contributions
of black people

00:29:28.920 --> 00:29:34.150
and the African people
to civilization.

00:29:34.150 --> 00:29:42.340
But I think that we were very
lucky because two years earlier,

00:29:42.340 --> 00:29:50.130
on June 16th 1966, our good
friend Stokely Carmichael Aquame

00:29:50.130 --> 00:29:55.800
Toure put out the
slogan of black power.

00:29:55.800 --> 00:30:02.260
And it spread like wildfire in
terms of the black community.

00:30:02.260 --> 00:30:06.680
And basically at least
at the cultural level

00:30:06.680 --> 00:30:10.380
and at the intellectual
level, black people began

00:30:10.380 --> 00:30:16.800
to define themselves as not only
beautiful in a physical sense,

00:30:16.800 --> 00:30:23.040
but beautiful in every sense of
people who made contributions.

00:30:23.040 --> 00:30:25.360
So that when Drum and
Spear Press and Drum

00:30:25.360 --> 00:30:29.820
and Spear Bookstore and the
Center for Black Education

00:30:29.820 --> 00:30:36.540
and other entities that we
created came into being,

00:30:36.540 --> 00:30:38.930
we brought it into
an environment

00:30:38.930 --> 00:30:43.930
that black people were hungry
to be able to assert themselves

00:30:43.930 --> 00:30:48.550
as people who made
contributions to civilizations.

00:30:48.550 --> 00:30:57.880
I think that the purpose of Drum
and Spear and all its aspects,

00:30:57.880 --> 00:31:01.870
which is the power to
define, is still the situation

00:31:01.870 --> 00:31:03.680
that we have to deal with.

00:31:03.680 --> 00:31:07.950
I listened to the previous
panel on Appalachia and one

00:31:07.950 --> 00:31:12.370
of the comments that was
made about Appalachia,

00:31:12.370 --> 00:31:16.240
about black people -- I mean,
and I look at what's going on

00:31:16.240 --> 00:31:20.000
and the discussion today
about the Supreme Court

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:24.430
and the question of
sexual abuse of women.

00:31:24.430 --> 00:31:30.770
That if you don't have the power
to define whether you're worthy

00:31:30.770 --> 00:31:33.770
in Appalachia or whether
you should be listed

00:31:33.770 --> 00:31:35.300
to about sexual assault,

00:31:35.300 --> 00:31:40.040
or whether you've made
contributions to civilization,

00:31:40.040 --> 00:31:42.600
you don't have the
power to define that.

00:31:42.600 --> 00:31:45.680
And you're always trying
to defend yourself.

00:31:45.680 --> 00:31:48.740
You will always be in a hole.

00:31:48.740 --> 00:31:53.140
So one of the things that's
important that we tried to do

00:31:53.140 --> 00:31:57.840
at Drum and Spear then and
we're trying to do now is trying

00:31:57.840 --> 00:32:03.020
to assert the power to define
who we are, what's important

00:32:03.020 --> 00:32:06.250
and how we should move
forward to make progress.

00:32:06.250 --> 00:32:09.830
&gt;&gt; Guha Shenkar:
Thank you, Courtland.

00:32:11.330 --> 00:32:15.150
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson: These issues
for us were, as you can see,

00:32:15.150 --> 00:32:17.480
not purely about
what we were doing

00:32:17.480 --> 00:32:21.490
in the sense of books or radio.

00:32:21.490 --> 00:32:26.200
But it was fueled by
this why we're doing it.

00:32:26.200 --> 00:32:29.150
And in that sense I think
we thought of ourselves

00:32:29.150 --> 00:32:33.060
as educators with a little
e, that we saw ourselves

00:32:33.060 --> 00:32:35.320
as really being in the
business of education.

00:32:35.320 --> 00:32:38.150
And it was no mistake that
we were affiliated then

00:32:38.150 --> 00:32:41.950
with the Center for Black
Education in that respect.

00:32:41.950 --> 00:32:45.650
And there were other places as
well that we were connected to.

00:32:45.650 --> 00:32:51.120
And that it was no mistake
that books would be sort

00:32:51.120 --> 00:32:53.220
of the focus of this initially.

00:32:53.220 --> 00:32:58.610
Courtland and Charlie and I had
worked together in the movement

00:32:58.610 --> 00:33:02.270
with the Student Nonviolent
Coordinating Committee or SNCC

00:33:02.270 --> 00:33:04.720
in Mississippi and Alabama.

00:33:04.720 --> 00:33:07.880
And particularly in
Alabama we had found

00:33:07.880 --> 00:33:13.450
that it was really helpful
to this defining oneself,

00:33:13.450 --> 00:33:17.460
defining what you wanted
to do, was really helpful.

00:33:17.460 --> 00:33:21.400
And that we started
creating our own books there.

00:33:21.400 --> 00:33:23.940
We created comic books as a way

00:33:23.940 --> 00:33:27.190
of educating the
would-be black voters

00:33:27.190 --> 00:33:29.780
and would-be politicians there

00:33:29.780 --> 00:33:33.300
about why complain
about the sheriff?

00:33:33.300 --> 00:33:35.450
Why not be the sheriff?

00:33:35.450 --> 00:33:38.890
And then people would say,
"But what's the sheriff's job?

00:33:38.890 --> 00:33:41.660
We don't know what
the sheriff does."

00:33:41.660 --> 00:33:45.900
So we would then take the
information and make it

00:33:45.900 --> 00:33:49.220
into a comic book about,
here's the role of the sheriff.

00:33:49.220 --> 00:33:51.380
Here's the role of
the tax assessor.

00:33:51.380 --> 00:33:54.540
And then over time, people
ran for those positions

00:33:54.540 --> 00:33:58.940
and became the tax assessor
and became the sheriff.

00:33:58.940 --> 00:34:04.330
So these rudimentary comics
were very, very beneficial,

00:34:04.330 --> 00:34:08.100
and that that was sort of
the beginning of our sort

00:34:08.100 --> 00:34:11.670
of working collaboration
in that way.

00:34:11.670 --> 00:34:14.680
And I was an amateur artist.

00:34:14.680 --> 00:34:16.910
I never had any formal training.

00:34:16.910 --> 00:34:21.670
But one of the other things that
I think was really so defining

00:34:21.670 --> 00:34:26.120
about all of us is a
kind of can-do spirit.

00:34:26.120 --> 00:34:29.630
It wasn't a question of, "Well,
I don't know how to do this."

00:34:29.630 --> 00:34:33.310
I mean, you've heard that all
down the line, of Judy saying,

00:34:33.310 --> 00:34:34.740
"Well, I've never
done this before."

00:34:34.740 --> 00:34:36.040
Tony, the same.

00:34:36.040 --> 00:34:38.090
The same was true of me.

00:34:38.090 --> 00:34:42.150
And then even after we
had established Drum

00:34:42.150 --> 00:34:46.040
and Spear bookstore, the
question was, what's missing?

00:34:46.040 --> 00:34:47.530
We need books.

00:34:47.530 --> 00:34:50.510
We need our own books,
not just the books

00:34:50.510 --> 00:34:53.900
that are being sold
by other publishers.

00:34:53.900 --> 00:34:55.920
We need our own books.

00:34:55.920 --> 00:34:58.420
And so we started creating them.

00:34:58.420 --> 00:35:02.980
And we had the good fortune
to have CLR James around,

00:35:02.980 --> 00:35:06.600
and so we then published
CLR James',

00:35:06.600 --> 00:35:09.000
A History of Pan-Africa Revolt.

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:11.840
We said, "We need new
children's books."

00:35:11.840 --> 00:35:17.260
So Courtland and a teacher, a
DC school teacher, Daphne Mews,

00:35:17.260 --> 00:35:20.350
a group of us got together
and started brainstorming

00:35:20.350 --> 00:35:23.430
about what is it that
we would tell kids?

00:35:23.430 --> 00:35:25.840
And we created then
the book, all right?

00:35:25.840 --> 00:35:30.280
We'd illustrate and we would
write the text together.

00:35:30.280 --> 00:35:33.560
We did the same thing
with our folk tales.

00:35:33.560 --> 00:35:37.160
And the people in
Tanzania were visiting

00:35:37.160 --> 00:35:39.770
and found it quite impressive.

00:35:39.770 --> 00:35:43.120
And we found ourselves
invited to Dar Es Salaam,

00:35:43.120 --> 00:35:48.190
Tanzania to help establish
a publishing company there.

00:35:48.190 --> 00:35:54.070
And the publishing venture
continues to this day.

00:35:54.070 --> 00:35:58.470
Our invitation to Tanzania
came also in association

00:35:58.470 --> 00:36:01.980
with the Sixth Pan-African
Congress which Courtland

00:36:01.980 --> 00:36:04.470
and several other people
helped to establish.

00:36:04.470 --> 00:36:08.440
So it was this, the work
that we were doing both

00:36:08.440 --> 00:36:14.260
in creating a publishing company
or in creating the bookstore,

00:36:14.260 --> 00:36:18.070
were things that then continued
to inspire other people.

00:36:18.070 --> 00:36:22.130
And it was wonderful to see
them move on to do these things.

00:36:22.130 --> 00:36:26.050
Somebody sort of said, "Well,
what would it look like today?"

00:36:26.050 --> 00:36:29.250
And one of the things that
we are very clear about is

00:36:29.250 --> 00:36:32.630
that again, it's the
why, not the what.

00:36:32.630 --> 00:36:37.630
And we all have been very
active in the last few years

00:36:37.630 --> 00:36:41.270
in creating what is called
the SNCC digital gateway,

00:36:41.270 --> 00:36:44.920
which is a website that
tells then the story

00:36:44.920 --> 00:36:47.590
of the Student Nonviolent
Coordinating Committee.

00:36:47.590 --> 00:36:52.240
And goes on to talk about what
young activists are doing today.

00:36:52.240 --> 00:37:00.650
So that's the story of Drum and
Spear Press, and I look forward

00:37:00.650 --> 00:37:05.650
to after Josh, to hearing
questions from others too.

00:37:07.750 --> 00:37:09.050
&gt;&gt; Joshua Davis: Okay.

00:37:09.050 --> 00:37:11.740
Yeah, I wanted to just
thank Guha and thank John

00:37:11.740 --> 00:37:14.440
and thank Thea and
everyone at the AFC

00:37:14.440 --> 00:37:16.010
for putting this together.

00:37:16.010 --> 00:37:18.380
Really great event.

00:37:18.380 --> 00:37:24.810
And I want to talk about Drum
and Spear, but just emphasize

00:37:24.810 --> 00:37:26.790
that of course what we've
been talking about grew

00:37:26.790 --> 00:37:28.970
out of the Civil
Rights Movement.

00:37:28.970 --> 00:37:32.380
It grew out of organizations
like SNCC

00:37:32.380 --> 00:37:35.570
and also was very much a part
of the Black Power Movement.

00:37:35.570 --> 00:37:41.600
And I think especially
in years '66, '67, '68,

00:37:41.600 --> 00:37:44.620
there wasn't always
necessarily a clear line

00:37:44.620 --> 00:37:47.570
between the two there,
overlapping.

00:37:47.570 --> 00:37:50.390
And kind of the big point
I wanted to make today --

00:37:50.390 --> 00:37:53.770
and I wonder, do you think we
could switch to the PowerPoint?

00:37:53.770 --> 00:37:58.750
Yeah. The point I was going to
make is that I think there's

00:37:58.750 --> 00:38:01.780
as lot of discussion
in recent years

00:38:01.780 --> 00:38:05.100
about how skewed
Americans' understanding

00:38:05.100 --> 00:38:07.450
of the Civil Rights Movement is.

00:38:07.450 --> 00:38:10.890
And how the public's
understanding has really lagged

00:38:10.890 --> 00:38:14.570
behind the participants'
understanding.

00:38:14.570 --> 00:38:18.820
And I would say the scholarship
has gotten much, much better.

00:38:18.820 --> 00:38:21.370
But most Americans,
if they know anything

00:38:21.370 --> 00:38:23.890
about the Civil Rights Movement,
they think of it as a movement

00:38:23.890 --> 00:38:26.900
for political change,
for social change.

00:38:26.900 --> 00:38:29.030
But what I was going
to say is one

00:38:29.030 --> 00:38:33.920
of the real neglected
legacies is that Civil Rights

00:38:33.920 --> 00:38:37.590
and Black Power were movements
for intellectual change.

00:38:37.590 --> 00:38:40.560
And I think Drum and Spear
really epitomizes that.

00:38:40.560 --> 00:38:43.900
And so I wanted to start
with a brief quote.

00:38:43.900 --> 00:38:47.480
It's from the New York Amsterdam
News which most people will know

00:38:47.480 --> 00:38:50.330
as kind of one of the premier
black newspapers in the country.

00:38:50.330 --> 00:38:54.150
The quote's from 1972.

00:38:54.150 --> 00:38:58.000
"Anyone who walks
along 100 25th Street

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:02.110
in Harlem today may be
impressed by the market changes

00:39:02.110 --> 00:39:05.540
from the Harlem Street
of yesterday.

00:39:05.540 --> 00:39:09.160
There are black-owned
clothing stores, record shops,

00:39:09.160 --> 00:39:13.740
bookstores, African bazaars
and other cultural happenings

00:39:13.740 --> 00:39:17.560
that now indicate a new
pride and self-determination

00:39:17.560 --> 00:39:19.480
in the black community.

00:39:19.480 --> 00:39:21.350
These changes in
the face of Harlem

00:39:21.350 --> 00:39:24.780
and other similar communities
are largely the result

00:39:24.780 --> 00:39:27.480
of a black revolution
of the mind,

00:39:27.480 --> 00:39:30.610
begun less than a decade ago."

00:39:30.610 --> 00:39:33.690
I think that's a quote
that I think really --

00:39:33.690 --> 00:39:35.710
this idea of the black
revolution of the mind.

00:39:35.710 --> 00:39:39.900
I think that's a large part of
what Drum and Spear was doing.

00:39:39.900 --> 00:39:44.010
And you know, I think a
lot of different parts

00:39:44.010 --> 00:39:46.240
of the Black Freedom
Struggle are doing this,

00:39:46.240 --> 00:39:48.870
the black arts movement
for example.

00:39:50.080 --> 00:39:53.220
In SNCC for example, I'm sure
a lot of people have heard

00:39:53.220 --> 00:39:55.410
of the Mississippi
Freedom Summer,

00:39:55.410 --> 00:39:57.490
and one of the large
parts of that effort

00:39:57.490 --> 00:40:01.110
in 1964 were the
Freedom Schools.

00:40:01.110 --> 00:40:03.020
And the Freedom Schools
which a lot

00:40:03.020 --> 00:40:04.460
of SNCC people were
involved with,

00:40:04.460 --> 00:40:07.360
and Charlie Cobb was
very involved with,

00:40:07.360 --> 00:40:12.740
I think there are seeds of Drum
and Spear in the Freedom School.

00:40:13.810 --> 00:40:19.510
And so Drum and Spear, like I
was saying, was not only part

00:40:19.510 --> 00:40:22.000
of the Civil Rights Movement,
the Black Power Movement,

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:25.710
but also two movements that I
talk about in my book called

00:40:25.710 --> 00:40:27.760
From Head Shops to Whole
Foods: The Rise and Fall

00:40:27.760 --> 00:40:29.290
of Activist Entrepreneurs.

