00:42:27.410 --> 00:42:31.400
So Drum and Spear was
part of what I would call

00:42:31.400 --> 00:42:36.050
that activist business movement
which is businesses growing

00:42:36.050 --> 00:42:39.580
out of not only the Black Power
Movement, but feminist movement,

00:42:39.580 --> 00:42:42.030
antiwar movement, even
the hippie movement,

00:42:42.030 --> 00:42:43.330
environmental movement.

00:42:43.330 --> 00:42:45.580
Activists who were
starting businesses.

00:42:45.580 --> 00:42:50.190
They're thinking of businesses
less as moneymaking ventures

00:42:50.190 --> 00:42:52.060
and more as organizing tools.

00:42:52.060 --> 00:42:54.710
They are interested in
keeping the lights on,

00:42:54.710 --> 00:42:56.640
but that's what my
book is about.

00:42:56.640 --> 00:42:58.070
And yeah, if anyone
wants to check it out,

00:42:58.070 --> 00:42:59.790
I've got copies back there.

00:42:59.790 --> 00:43:03.320
But getting back to this idea

00:43:03.320 --> 00:43:08.010
of also I would say a
black bookstore movement.

00:43:08.010 --> 00:43:15.500
So obviously there were black
authors going back centuries.

00:43:15.500 --> 00:43:16.830
But in the United States,

00:43:16.830 --> 00:43:21.220
the kind of mainstream literary
marketplace, other than people

00:43:21.220 --> 00:43:28.460
like Ralph Ellison, Langston
Hughes, the real heavyweights --

00:43:28.460 --> 00:43:31.500
they were just a
few marquee authors

00:43:31.500 --> 00:43:33.290
who were getting any attention

00:43:33.290 --> 00:43:37.010
from the white-dominated
literary marketplace

00:43:37.010 --> 00:43:38.310
in the early-'60's.

00:43:38.310 --> 00:43:43.030
And in the early-'60s, I think
I found there was maybe a dozen

00:43:43.030 --> 00:43:46.310
what we could call black-owned
and black-oriented bookstores

00:43:46.310 --> 00:43:47.610
in the whole United States.

00:43:47.610 --> 00:43:49.300
Roughly a dozen.

00:43:49.300 --> 00:43:52.510
But those numbers began
booming in the middle

00:43:52.510 --> 00:43:54.510
and especially late-'60's.

00:43:54.510 --> 00:43:57.800
Really they're inseparable
from the Black Power era.

00:43:57.800 --> 00:44:00.330
So what was a dozen stores

00:44:00.330 --> 00:44:04.380
in say the early-'60's
became something

00:44:04.380 --> 00:44:06.970
like 75 stores ten years later.

00:44:06.970 --> 00:44:09.820
And it's a big jump
from 12 to 75.

00:44:09.820 --> 00:44:13.960
In 1969, New York Times
-- am I getting a warning?

00:44:13.960 --> 00:44:15.260
Two minutes, okay.

00:44:15.260 --> 00:44:20.420
1969, New York Times
did a story.

00:44:20.420 --> 00:44:23.480
This kind of goes to the point
Judy was making, just the fact

00:44:23.480 --> 00:44:27.440
that the New York Times would
do a story on the novelty

00:44:27.440 --> 00:44:31.460
of black people selling
books to black people.

00:44:31.460 --> 00:44:34.020
That was a novel going-on.

00:44:34.020 --> 00:44:38.220
And the Times said, "A surge
of book-buying is sweeping

00:44:38.220 --> 00:44:43.340
through black communities
across the country."

00:44:43.340 --> 00:44:45.790
And the whole piece was
about black-owned bookstores.

00:44:45.790 --> 00:44:47.510
And there were these
old stalwarts

00:44:47.510 --> 00:44:51.100
like Lewis Michaux's Books
in Harlem, his store.

00:44:51.100 --> 00:44:52.480
But there are stores
popping up all

00:44:52.480 --> 00:44:55.120
over the countries
in DC, in Atlanta.

00:44:55.120 --> 00:44:58.190
More in Harlem and Brooklyn.

00:44:58.190 --> 00:45:00.150
And there's a few that
still even exist today.

00:45:00.150 --> 00:45:02.510
Marcus Books comes
out of San Francisco

00:45:02.510 --> 00:45:06.240
and they still have a
store in Oakland today.

00:45:06.240 --> 00:45:08.130
Vaughn's bookstore in Detroit.

00:45:08.130 --> 00:45:12.860
Okay, so black-owned bookstores
are promoting self-education.

00:45:12.860 --> 00:45:16.570
They are promoting
self-definition.

00:45:16.570 --> 00:45:18.540
They are in a sense
information centers

00:45:18.540 --> 00:45:20.810
for the Black Power Movement.

00:45:20.810 --> 00:45:24.550
And they are, like I
mentioned, part of a movement

00:45:24.550 --> 00:45:25.850
for intellectual change.

00:45:25.850 --> 00:45:31.010
If you just look at the books on
this one page of this catalog,

00:45:31.010 --> 00:45:33.190
it's some of those
exact same people.

00:45:33.190 --> 00:45:35.860
So I don't think J. A.
Rogers is on this page.

00:45:35.860 --> 00:45:39.550
