it's from 1968.

00:45:52.250 --> 00:45:55.600
I think there's at least a
Julius Wester title on here

00:45:55.600 --> 00:45:58.180
that is published
in '68 I think.

00:45:58.180 --> 00:46:01.190
But I mean, it's
DuBois, it's St. Clair,

00:46:01.190 --> 00:46:04.290
Drake, E. Franklin Fraser.

00:46:04.290 --> 00:46:05.720
Howard Zin is on there, right?

00:46:05.720 --> 00:46:08.050
Howard Zin having been the
first person to write a book

00:46:08.050 --> 00:46:12.290
about SNCC I think, and had
himself been involved in SNCC.

00:46:12.290 --> 00:46:15.680
And maybe Julius Wester is
not on this page actually.

00:46:15.680 --> 00:46:19.390
But this is the dimension
of the Civil Rights Movement

00:46:19.390 --> 00:46:23.870
that I think most Americans
are not aware of, this movement

00:46:23.870 --> 00:46:25.170
for intellectual change.

00:46:25.170 --> 00:46:26.750
And it's been something
that's been occurring to me.

00:46:26.750 --> 00:46:30.460
I'm just wrapping up very
belatedly a Taylor Branch

00:46:30.460 --> 00:46:35.000
trilogy on MLK which if
you put the books together

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:36.600
and the type is tiny.

00:46:36.600 --> 00:46:42.130
But just really drove home
for me also like Dr. King,

00:46:42.130 --> 00:46:45.350
remembered as a Civil Rights
leader, as a master orator,

00:46:45.350 --> 00:46:49.230
as a minister, as a moral
force, as a nonviolent force.

00:46:49.230 --> 00:46:52.110
But he really was
an intellectual also

00:46:52.110 --> 00:46:54.280
and I think that's
just been forgotten.

00:46:54.280 --> 00:46:56.500
But he was an intellectual.

00:46:56.500 --> 00:46:59.000
That was such a big
part of who he was.

00:46:59.000 --> 00:47:02.110
And so I'll just end
it on that, yeah.

