There are marches
and demonstrations,

00:55:20.110 --> 00:55:26.350
all of which are good
and strong and such.

00:55:26.350 --> 00:55:28.150
There's a lot of opinion.

00:55:28.150 --> 00:55:32.220
But what to do, what do you do
when you get up in the morning

00:55:32.220 --> 00:55:34.440
to combat this insanity

00:55:34.440 --> 00:55:39.380
that we're facing I think
is still being developed.

00:55:39.380 --> 00:55:42.990
That there is the
vote, you know.

00:55:42.990 --> 00:55:48.150
Folks can vote and
put Republicans out

00:55:48.150 --> 00:55:50.250
and the Democrats in
and that's all good.

00:55:50.250 --> 00:55:52.360
But there's a personal
frustration that I have

00:55:52.360 --> 00:55:53.660
about what is there --

00:55:53.660 --> 00:55:55.910
eventually you get tired
of hearing people talk.

00:55:55.910 --> 00:55:57.950
You know, I get tired
of hearing people talk.

00:55:57.950 --> 00:55:59.740
I get tired of hearing
myself talk,

00:55:59.740 --> 00:56:01.210
you know, much less others.

00:56:01.210 --> 00:56:05.180
And there's a difference
between talking and doing.

00:56:05.180 --> 00:56:08.600
What happened around Drum
and Spear was a lot of doing.

00:56:08.600 --> 00:56:10.870
There was a lot of doing.

00:56:10.870 --> 00:56:15.710
I mean, what it took to build

00:56:15.710 --> 00:56:21.270
and maintain back then
was constant work.

00:56:21.270 --> 00:56:27.020
And I don't know
of a place now --

00:56:27.020 --> 00:56:28.510
I don't know of every
place, obviously.

00:56:28.510 --> 00:56:29.810
There might be.

00:56:29.810 --> 00:56:31.110
I'm sure they're out there.

00:56:31.110 --> 00:56:33.550
Young people are doing
all kinds of things.

00:56:33.550 --> 00:56:36.630
But it's what to do
to make the difference

00:56:36.630 --> 00:56:39.490
that at least to
me is not clear.

00:56:45.240 --> 00:56:47.090
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: See, it's
interesting when Jennifer talks

00:56:47.090 --> 00:56:51.640
about how three of us
have gone into media.

00:56:51.640 --> 00:56:58.270
I mean, Jennifer really was
really major in PBS and CBB

00:56:58.270 --> 00:57:01.060
and some of the funding
that Apple Shop talked

00:57:01.060 --> 00:57:04.530
about that was coming
through Jennifer's shop.

00:57:04.530 --> 00:57:08.820
Tony all these years has
been doing DC film festivals.

00:57:08.820 --> 00:57:11.790
And you know, when
I worked on Eyes

00:57:11.790 --> 00:57:13.480
on the Prize, it
was all 14 hours.

00:57:13.480 --> 00:57:17.440
And one of the things I wanted
to do in that second series

00:57:17.440 --> 00:57:19.430
of eight hours -- because
the first series is six hours

00:57:19.430 --> 00:57:24.940
and the second is eight hours
-- we had a chance of doing --

00:57:24.940 --> 00:57:29.950
we all talked as a team about
what college takeover do you do.

00:57:29.950 --> 00:57:31.400
We could have done
San Francisco State.

00:57:31.400 --> 00:57:33.340
We could have done Cornell.

00:57:33.340 --> 00:57:35.820
And I said to Henry Hampton,
the head of Blackside

00:57:35.820 --> 00:57:38.320
which was the production
company that did it --

00:57:38.320 --> 00:57:40.310
I said, "You know,
sometimes we're not talking

00:57:40.310 --> 00:57:41.610
to white folks.

00:57:41.610 --> 00:57:42.910
We're talking to each other."

00:57:42.910 --> 00:57:46.040
And so for me it was we need to
do Howard University takeover.

00:57:46.040 --> 00:57:49.580
And that's why that Howard
University takeover story is

00:57:49.580 --> 00:57:51.340
in Eyes on the Prize.

00:57:51.340 --> 00:57:54.350
By the way, all 14 hours of
Eyes on the Prize is on YouTube.

00:57:54.350 --> 00:57:57.180
I have to just mention that.

00:57:57.180 --> 00:58:02.480
And I think part
of the -- say what?

00:58:02.480 --> 00:58:04.370
You got it.

00:58:04.370 --> 00:58:07.350
I mean, given that PBS doesn't
do diddly-squat with it,

00:58:07.350 --> 00:58:09.720
it's good that it's on YouTube.

00:58:09.720 --> 00:58:12.520
But I think that the other part

00:58:12.520 --> 00:58:14.030
of it though is how
you organize.

00:58:14.030 --> 00:58:17.150
And I think we always understood

00:58:17.150 --> 00:58:20.390
that nothing replaces
the door-to-door.

00:58:20.390 --> 00:58:23.000
Nothing replaces going
to everybody so that --

00:58:23.000 --> 00:58:24.760
I mean, one of the
things that Beto O'Rourke

00:58:24.760 --> 00:58:27.500
in Texas understands is that
he's gone through every one

00:58:27.500 --> 00:58:31.310
of those counties in Texas.

00:58:31.310 --> 00:58:36.280
That social media can be really
helpful if you use it as a tool,

00:58:36.280 --> 00:58:38.030
but if you don't understand
that people are going

00:58:38.030 --> 00:58:41.210
to put their lives on the line
for you, or their economics

00:58:41.210 --> 00:58:44.440
or whatever it is, that
they've got to know who you are.

00:58:44.440 --> 00:58:48.450
And they cannot know that
through Twitter or whoever.

00:58:48.450 --> 00:58:49.750
They've got to see you

00:58:49.750 --> 00:58:51.400
and they've got to
see you in action.

00:58:51.400 --> 00:58:54.110
And social media is not
going to do that part

00:58:54.110 --> 00:58:57.020
of it for you I think.

00:58:57.020 --> 00:58:58.740
&gt;&gt; Guha Shenkar: And I
was struck by something

00:58:58.740 --> 00:59:01.430
on Josh's reading list that's
there, and then looking

00:59:01.430 --> 00:59:03.480
at what you have in the
table in front of you.

00:59:03.480 --> 00:59:07.730
Obviously these books are sort
of for a high political theory,

00:59:07.730 --> 00:59:09.810
CLR James and Herbert
Afthaker and so on,

00:59:09.810 --> 00:59:13.280
so there's that reaching
people who have been educated

00:59:13.280 --> 00:59:16.720
to some extent or who have
the capacity and the interest

00:59:16.720 --> 00:59:19.530
in hearing about these kinds
of intellectual perspectives

00:59:19.530 --> 00:59:22.310
and rather high theoretical
positions.

00:59:22.310 --> 00:59:26.030
But then the Watoto Africa
and the children's books,

00:59:26.030 --> 00:59:28.430
you seem to be getting them
from the sort of cradle to --

00:59:28.430 --> 00:59:31.010
not quite grave, if
you know what I mean.

00:59:31.010 --> 00:59:32.310
[ Laughter ]

00:59:32.310 --> 00:59:33.610
You know, sort of my age.

00:59:33.610 --> 00:59:34.990
Not sure if it's the grave
or not, but can you speak

00:59:34.990 --> 00:59:36.550
about that just a little bit?

00:59:36.550 --> 00:59:38.300
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson: Well, it's
interesting, one of the things

00:59:38.300 --> 00:59:43.480
that we at SNCC were known for
was sort of telling our history

00:59:43.480 --> 00:59:46.180
from the inside out
and from the bottom up.

00:59:46.180 --> 00:59:50.530
And so that in part relates
to the notion that we believe

00:59:50.530 --> 00:59:53.420
that everybody that we
work with was important,

00:59:53.420 --> 00:59:56.230
and that we didn't
make distinctions

00:59:56.230 --> 00:59:58.730
between the sharecroppers
or the people

00:59:58.730 --> 01:00:00.640
who were the school principals

01:00:00.640 --> 01:00:02.340
in the areas that
we worked with.

01:00:02.340 --> 01:00:04.910
And in some cases, like
with the Freedom Schools

01:00:04.910 --> 01:00:06.820
that were mentioned,
and some of the work

01:00:06.820 --> 01:00:09.400
that we subsequently did,
we put a lot of emphasis

01:00:09.400 --> 01:00:13.860
on adult education and on
literacy, because that was part

01:00:13.860 --> 01:00:18.170
of the legacy of the
segregation and the horrors

01:00:18.170 --> 01:00:19.860
that people had lived through.

01:00:19.860 --> 01:00:23.400
And that it was the
thirst for knowledge,

01:00:23.400 --> 01:00:25.260
the thirst for information.

01:00:25.260 --> 01:00:26.760
It's just incredible.

01:00:26.760 --> 01:00:31.080
And so the kinds of discussions
that we would have in SNCC

01:00:31.080 --> 01:00:33.690
and with people with
whom we were working

01:00:33.690 --> 01:00:37.030
in these rural areas
was quite astonishing.

01:00:37.030 --> 01:00:39.800
Because people really
wanted to learn.

01:00:39.800 --> 01:00:41.690
They wanted to talk about ideas.

01:00:41.690 --> 01:00:44.730
They wanted to talk
about a range of things.

01:00:44.730 --> 01:00:47.930
And so that was what these works

01:00:47.930 --> 01:00:51.650
in part we were creating
them for.

01:00:51.650 --> 01:00:53.450
&gt;&gt; Tony Gittens: I'd like
to step back a little bit

01:00:53.450 --> 01:00:55.310
from what I just
said, that the folks

01:00:55.310 --> 01:01:02.750
who I think are really doing
something are the teens

01:01:02.750 --> 01:01:04.080
from the high school where --

01:01:04.080 --> 01:01:05.380
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson:
Yes, Parkland.

01:01:05.380 --> 01:01:06.680
&gt;&gt; Tony Gittens: Parkland.

01:01:06.680 --> 01:01:07.980
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: Yeah, honey.

01:01:07.980 --> 01:01:09.280
&gt;&gt; Tony Gittens: Yes.

01:01:09.280 --> 01:01:12.820
That when we were watching
them, they did remind us,

01:01:12.820 --> 01:01:15.860
the did remind me of some

01:01:15.860 --> 01:01:18.660
of the activity we've been
talking about here today.

01:01:18.660 --> 01:01:23.150
That those kids are smart and
they work hard and they're

01:01:23.150 --> 01:01:25.660
out there and they put
their heart and their soul

01:01:25.660 --> 01:01:29.910
into doing something to
change, to make that shift

01:01:29.910 --> 01:01:32.280
about defining that
Courtland was talking about.

01:01:32.280 --> 01:01:36.030
The question with
them is, do they --

01:01:36.030 --> 01:01:38.060
and I'm sure they -- all right.

01:01:38.060 --> 01:01:40.900
Do they know -- and this
is something we learned,

01:01:40.900 --> 01:01:42.640
it's a long-term struggle.

01:01:42.640 --> 01:01:44.970
That the enemy is dug in.

01:01:44.970 --> 01:01:47.600
The NRA in their case is dug in.

01:01:47.600 --> 01:01:52.080
Those guys and girls
fight for every inch

01:01:52.080 --> 01:01:54.220
of holding onto those guns.

01:01:54.220 --> 01:01:58.670
And it's going to take a while
to beat those folks back.

01:01:58.670 --> 01:02:01.650
But I would say that
they're doing something,

01:02:01.650 --> 01:02:05.120
that those young kids
are doing something.

01:02:05.120 --> 01:02:07.030
&gt;&gt; Guha Shenkar: I want
to shift gears slightly.

01:02:07.030 --> 01:02:09.180
Josh, did you have
something to add to that?

01:02:09.180 --> 01:02:10.480
&gt;&gt; Joshua Davis:
Yeah, just briefly,

01:02:10.480 --> 01:02:14.120
I was going to say we just kind
of can't overemphasize the point

01:02:14.120 --> 01:02:15.500
about this being pre-internet.

01:02:15.500 --> 01:02:16.900
I think we are all
aware of that.

01:02:16.900 --> 01:02:19.110
But I always have
to really emphasize

01:02:19.110 --> 01:02:21.600
that with students,
what that meant.

01:02:21.600 --> 01:02:24.940
I mean, if you wanted to learn
about political movements,

01:02:24.940 --> 01:02:28.790
you've basically learned
about it either through books

01:02:28.790 --> 01:02:31.900
or more likely through people
and the people around you,

01:02:31.900 --> 01:02:34.810
people you went to school with,
people you went to church with.

01:02:34.810 --> 01:02:37.020
And these activist
businesses, and Drum

01:02:37.020 --> 01:02:38.640
and Spear really epitomize this.

01:02:38.640 --> 01:02:41.070
They were focused
on the three P's.

01:02:41.070 --> 01:02:43.470
First of all they wanted
to put new products out.

01:02:43.470 --> 01:02:46.140
They wanted to put
political products out there.

01:02:46.140 --> 01:02:48.780
Books by black authors
that are almost unavailable

01:02:48.780 --> 01:02:50.490
in American society.

01:02:50.490 --> 01:02:52.200
Then they wanted to
focus on the processes.

01:02:52.200 --> 01:02:54.780
So this wasn't just a
book store, but Drum

01:02:54.780 --> 01:02:57.990
and Spear had a radio show,
and the publishing press,

01:02:57.990 --> 01:03:03.040
and they're linking up with
publishers in Tanzania, right?

01:03:03.040 --> 01:03:05.230
So they're reinventing
processes.

01:03:05.230 --> 01:03:07.800
But place, place was
really, really important

01:03:07.800 --> 01:03:10.410
and I think place is
still very important,

01:03:10.410 --> 01:03:14.360
but I think especially then
without people being able

01:03:14.360 --> 01:03:17.120
to connect through a thing like
the internet, through a thing

01:03:17.120 --> 01:03:20.380
like Twitter, you
needed to meet in person.

01:03:20.380 --> 01:03:22.880
And it was very hard
to find a gateway

01:03:22.880 --> 01:03:24.670
into movements, into literature.

01:03:24.670 --> 01:03:28.770
And I remember Judy saying
this before: the bookstore was

01:03:28.770 --> 01:03:33.410
for the community, and you
know, DC was chocolate city.

01:03:33.410 --> 01:03:36.090
But there's still
class segregation even

01:03:36.090 --> 01:03:38.050
within black DC.

01:03:38.050 --> 01:03:41.170
And so a place like Howard which
is like the shining institution

01:03:41.170 --> 01:03:44.330
on the hill was very, very
distant from a lot of people

01:03:44.330 --> 01:03:45.630
in the Columbia Heights
neighborhood.

01:03:45.630 --> 01:03:47.780
You had people coming into
the store who had never been

01:03:47.780 --> 01:03:49.970
to a bookstore before.

01:03:49.970 --> 01:03:54.850
And to have a public
facing political institution

01:03:54.850 --> 01:03:58.060
that sold some of these books
like these but had it kind

01:03:58.060 --> 01:04:01.960
of mediated through people
who could connect people

01:04:01.960 --> 01:04:06.190
on the ground to some of these
books, that was hugely important

01:04:06.190 --> 01:04:07.840
in a way that is
even more important

01:04:07.840 --> 01:04:09.870
than I think it would be today.

01:04:09.870 --> 01:04:11.900
Because people can
self-educate online.

01:04:11.900 --> 01:04:13.230
&gt;&gt; Guha Shenkar: Right.

01:04:13.230 --> 01:04:15.830
So we were talking
about the space

01:04:15.830 --> 01:04:17.130
of intellectual production.

01:04:17.130 --> 01:04:20.070
And I want to make
sure that those of you

01:04:20.070 --> 01:04:22.460
who don't already know this
story, even for those of us

01:04:22.460 --> 01:04:23.760
who do know the story,

01:04:23.760 --> 01:04:26.420
that intellectual
production is dangerous.

01:04:26.420 --> 01:04:28.290
It brings about certain
kinds of reprisals.

01:04:28.290 --> 01:04:31.990
It brings about certain
kinds of attention.

01:04:31.990 --> 01:04:35.410
And I think the point that Tony
is making about what the forces

01:04:35.410 --> 01:04:38.220
that are impinging upon you in
the first place and keep coming

01:04:38.220 --> 01:04:40.880
down on you are very real.

01:04:40.880 --> 01:04:43.570
And maybe I'll get
Josh to kick this off,

01:04:43.570 --> 01:04:46.620
because there's a really
intricate part of this book,

01:04:46.620 --> 01:04:50.620
From Head Shops to Whole
Foods, which is also excerpted

01:04:50.620 --> 01:04:53.430
in the Atlantic Magazine which I
wanted all of you to talk about.

01:04:53.430 --> 01:04:56.420
But can you talk a little
bit about exactly who it was

01:04:56.420 --> 01:04:59.870
and what were the kinds of
outcomes and effects from people

01:04:59.870 --> 01:05:04.070
in positions of power against
Drum and Spear and other kinds

01:05:04.070 --> 01:05:05.630
of entrepreneurs like that?

01:05:05.630 --> 01:05:06.930
&gt;&gt; Joshua Davis: All right.

01:05:06.930 --> 01:05:11.980
So I think again to go back to
this idea of these businesses,

01:05:11.980 --> 01:05:13.990
especially Drum and Spear
being the public face

01:05:13.990 --> 01:05:18.070
of a movement, as
Courtland said.

01:05:18.070 --> 01:05:20.480
Stokely was a dear
friend and people

01:05:20.480 --> 01:05:24.090
like the FBI were very
keenly interested in Stokely.

01:05:24.090 --> 01:05:25.850
I mean, they were
deeply interested in SNCC

01:05:25.850 --> 01:05:29.070
and the movement and
Dr. King and everyone.

01:05:29.070 --> 01:05:33.920
But in 1968, I think Stokely
was really one of the people

01:05:33.920 --> 01:05:37.110
that they were almost
obsessed with.

01:05:37.110 --> 01:05:40.220
And the dangers of him -- if
you've ever heard of this memo

01:05:40.220 --> 01:05:43.090
that J. Edgar Hoover
wrote about we've got

01:05:43.090 --> 01:05:46.450
to stop the possibility of
a rise of a black messiah.

01:05:46.450 --> 01:05:50.270
And what I kind of came up
with through my research was

01:05:50.270 --> 01:05:55.310
that as part of [inaudible],
part of the FBI really focusing

01:05:55.310 --> 01:05:58.400
on trying to disrupt
movements and especially trying

01:05:58.400 --> 01:06:02.210
to destroy Civil Rights
and Black Power Movements,

01:06:02.210 --> 01:06:03.510
they became very,
very interested

01:06:03.510 --> 01:06:05.040
in black-owned bookstores.

01:06:05.040 --> 01:06:10.050
And Hoover even issued a memo
to every local field office

01:06:10.050 --> 01:06:12.100
in the country and it said,

01:06:12.100 --> 01:06:15.880
watch out for what he called
African-type bookstores.

01:06:15.880 --> 01:06:20.370
"They're extremists, they're
hateful, they're anti-white.

01:06:20.370 --> 01:06:22.030
And if there's one
in your jurisdiction,

01:06:22.030 --> 01:06:23.980
you need to open a file
on them immediately."

01:06:23.980 --> 01:06:26.240
And that's maybe six months

01:06:26.240 --> 01:06:30.540
after the black messiah
memo of March 1968.

01:06:30.540 --> 01:06:33.260
But as it would just happen,

01:06:33.260 --> 01:06:36.960
Drum and Spear was conveniently
located not even five miles

01:06:36.960 --> 01:06:38.300
from the Federal Bureau

01:06:38.300 --> 01:06:40.920
of Investigation's
national headquarters.

01:06:40.920 --> 01:06:42.440
&gt;&gt; Guha Shenkar:
Strategy or tactics?

01:06:42.440 --> 01:06:43.740
&gt;&gt; Joshua Davis: Yeah.

01:06:43.740 --> 01:06:46.480
And you can imagine the FBI
agents were like, "Well,

01:06:46.480 --> 01:06:49.920
I guess we're the ones who only
have to drive three miles."

01:06:49.920 --> 01:06:51.960
And so they had all
kinds of interactions.

01:06:51.960 --> 01:06:56.930
And I think I found
probably FBI agents

01:06:56.930 --> 01:07:01.210
in at least half a dozen cities
doing surveillance and informing

01:07:01.210 --> 01:07:03.060
and spying on black-owned
bookstores.

01:07:03.060 --> 01:07:07.510
But there's probably
many more than that.

01:07:07.510 --> 01:07:10.130
[ Inaudible ]

01:07:10.130 --> 01:07:15.520
&gt;&gt; Guha Shenkar: Do you want to
talk about that a little bit?

01:07:15.520 --> 01:07:16.820
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: Okay, yeah.

01:07:16.820 --> 01:07:18.120
Okay.

01:07:18.120 --> 01:07:19.420
&gt;&gt; Tony Gittens: Okay, so they
used to come into the store.

01:07:19.420 --> 01:07:20.800
We found this out --
actually Josh dug this out.

01:07:20.800 --> 01:07:22.940
Josh is so talented.

01:07:22.940 --> 01:07:24.240
The man is a good man.

01:07:24.240 --> 01:07:25.710
Thank you, Josh, for
all you do, really.

01:07:25.710 --> 01:07:27.010
Really.

01:07:27.010 --> 01:07:28.310
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: Yes.

01:07:28.310 --> 01:07:30.000
&gt;&gt; Tony Gittens: So
Josh got the FBI records

01:07:30.000 --> 01:07:33.340
about their surveillance
of us at Drum and Sphere,

01:07:33.340 --> 01:07:35.130
which is fascinating reading.

01:07:35.130 --> 01:07:38.100
I read it twice late
one night when --

01:07:38.100 --> 01:07:40.700
I forgot, I think Josh
or Judy sent it to me.

01:07:40.700 --> 01:07:42.680
And it's just fascinating,
but they would come

01:07:42.680 --> 01:07:46.970
in in plain clothes and
engage us and buy books.

01:07:46.970 --> 01:07:49.140
And I think they had bought --

01:07:49.140 --> 01:07:51.410
I think Josh, you said they
had bought a whole bunch of --

01:07:51.410 --> 01:07:55.580
we were selling Mao's Little Red
Book and they bought them all

01:07:55.580 --> 01:07:59.040
and sat in the car
outside and read them.

01:07:59.040 --> 01:08:01.060
[ Laughter ]

01:08:01.060 --> 01:08:03.140
It got to the point
of being silly.

01:08:03.140 --> 01:08:06.000
But there are files on everybody
you see sitting up here,

01:08:06.000 --> 01:08:08.630
and many more, about
our comings and goings.

01:08:08.630 --> 01:08:10.670
I was surprised what they
knew about where I lived,

01:08:10.670 --> 01:08:13.910
who my social friends were.

01:08:13.910 --> 01:08:17.700
But they had a file on us.

01:08:17.700 --> 01:08:22.250
I mean, they were about to
bring us down if they could.

01:08:22.250 --> 01:08:24.900
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson: At
an earlier point too,

01:08:24.900 --> 01:08:27.070
when I was working
with SNCC in Atlanta

01:08:27.070 --> 01:08:30.070
and we had some financial
problems, I and a group

01:08:30.070 --> 01:08:32.830
of others -- SNCC people
had opened a little store,

01:08:32.830 --> 01:08:38.260
a little boutique near the
Atlanta University complex.

01:08:38.260 --> 01:08:41.260
And there are FBI
records too that show --

01:08:41.260 --> 01:08:46.860
in the records they talk
about then people coming

01:08:46.860 --> 01:08:49.870
into the store, their
agents coming into the store

01:08:49.870 --> 01:08:53.830
and overhearing things in
the store about you know,

01:08:53.830 --> 01:08:57.070
whether Stokely or
someone was coming to town.

01:08:57.070 --> 01:08:59.920
And it's really interesting
because then you know,

01:08:59.920 --> 01:09:06.650
the conversations that they
overheard helped us identify

01:09:06.650 --> 01:09:12.880
who then the agent was
in that particular case.

01:09:12.880 --> 01:09:16.150
But it was fascinating
to see this sort of trail

01:09:16.150 --> 01:09:20.640
of surveillance wherever
we were in that respect.

01:09:20.640 --> 01:09:22.740
It used to take a lot
of time to get back

01:09:22.740 --> 01:09:25.030
into the country
when we traveled.

01:09:25.030 --> 01:09:27.040
[ Laughter ]

01:09:27.040 --> 01:09:28.340
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson:
Can I also say,

01:09:28.340 --> 01:09:30.170
I don't know why they thought
that they could be undercover.

01:09:30.170 --> 01:09:34.240
At this point, you know,
we were not gentrified.

01:09:34.240 --> 01:09:37.350
I mean, only black people
came into Drum and Spear.

01:09:37.350 --> 01:09:39.630
And there were only white
agents at this point,

01:09:39.630 --> 01:09:40.930
and they always looked
like they used

01:09:40.930 --> 01:09:42.230
to in Greenwood, Mississippi.

01:09:42.230 --> 01:09:43.530
They had the funny little shoes

01:09:43.530 --> 01:09:45.520
and they always wore a
button down, and they walk in

01:09:45.520 --> 01:09:46.820
and they think that
we're not going to know

01:09:46.820 --> 01:09:48.120
that they're FBI agents.

01:09:48.120 --> 01:09:50.330
And you know, then they
pull stuff off the shelves

01:09:50.330 --> 01:09:52.580
that they clearly don't
even know what it is.

01:09:52.580 --> 01:09:54.060
You know, and then
they pile it up.

01:09:54.060 --> 01:09:56.220
Now most people used to
come into Drum and Spear

01:09:56.220 --> 01:09:57.730
and you'd have one or two books.

01:09:57.730 --> 01:09:59.030
They had piles of books

01:09:59.030 --> 01:10:00.980
that they're buying,
and they're white.

01:10:00.980 --> 01:10:04.030
So you know, we kind
of knew, yeah.

01:10:04.030 --> 01:10:06.040
[ Laughter ]

01:10:06.040 --> 01:10:07.340
&gt;&gt; Guha Shenkar:
So I like the fact

01:10:07.340 --> 01:10:10.510
that your sustainability model
is predicated on surveillance.

01:10:10.510 --> 01:10:13.110
[ Laughter ]

01:10:13.110 --> 01:10:14.830
Maybe the library's missing
a few on our circulation.

01:10:14.830 --> 01:10:16.130
I'm not quite sure.

01:10:16.130 --> 01:10:17.430
&gt;&gt; Tony Gittens: Bring them on.

01:10:17.430 --> 01:10:19.350
They also got into
our bank accounts.

01:10:19.350 --> 01:10:23.060
They went to the bank
where we did our banking

01:10:23.060 --> 01:10:24.360
and there were reports.

01:10:24.360 --> 01:10:27.340
There was some guy there who
sent them everything we did,

01:10:27.340 --> 01:10:29.890
all of our statements,
all of our activities,

01:10:29.890 --> 01:10:31.630
companies we were dealing with.

01:10:31.630 --> 01:10:33.760
I mean, all that's
just recorded.

01:10:33.760 --> 01:10:35.060
They were after us.

01:10:35.060 --> 01:10:37.850
They were after us hard.

01:10:37.850 --> 01:10:39.760
&gt;&gt; Guha Shenkar: So
I think we're coming

01:10:39.760 --> 01:10:41.510
to unfortunately the
end of the discussion.

01:10:41.510 --> 01:10:43.790
But I want to open it
up to folks out there.

01:10:43.790 --> 01:10:45.090
I mean, I have tons
more questions.

01:10:45.090 --> 01:10:47.120
I'm happy to keep talking
up here, but I'd really

01:10:47.120 --> 01:10:49.090
like to make sure that we
have this as a dialogue.

01:10:49.090 --> 01:10:51.130
And again we have the mics.

01:10:51.130 --> 01:10:54.850
So please, yes, Barry
is right here in front.

01:10:54.850 --> 01:10:57.900
&gt;&gt; I just had a question.

01:10:57.900 --> 01:11:04.470
In I guess '69 or '70 I
drove out here from Missouri

01:11:04.470 --> 01:11:07.800
to attend the DC Blues Festival.

01:11:07.800 --> 01:11:10.520
You mentioned Topper
Carew was the first person

01:11:10.520 --> 01:11:11.820
who put that together.

01:11:11.820 --> 01:11:14.470
It was one of maybe the first

01:11:14.470 --> 01:11:17.710
and only blues festival
put together

01:11:17.710 --> 01:11:20.460
by an African American
organization at that time.

01:11:20.460 --> 01:11:21.760
It seemed to me.

01:11:21.760 --> 01:11:24.530
Anyway, was that
connected in any way to Drum

01:11:24.530 --> 01:11:26.150
and Spear or to your work?

01:11:26.150 --> 01:11:27.450
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson: No.

01:11:27.450 --> 01:11:28.750
I was not formally connected.

01:11:28.750 --> 01:11:30.050
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

01:11:30.050 --> 01:11:31.350
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson: But
there were some wonderful

01:11:31.350 --> 01:11:33.220
organizations in
Washington DC at the time.

01:11:33.220 --> 01:11:35.640
And Karen Spellman and a group

01:11:35.640 --> 01:11:38.910
of other people are
developing a collection

01:11:38.910 --> 01:11:41.970
of materials online
that's called the Black

01:11:41.970 --> 01:11:43.450
Power Chronicles.

01:11:43.450 --> 01:11:46.040
And it's about some of
the cultural activities

01:11:46.040 --> 01:11:48.770
that were taking
place in Washington DC

01:11:48.770 --> 01:11:52.960
from like 1966 on
up to present day.

01:11:52.960 --> 01:11:56.150
And that Topper Carew,
and I've forgotten

01:11:56.150 --> 01:11:59.910
who else he was working
with, had the new thing.

01:11:59.910 --> 01:12:01.680
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson:
Alice Carew later.

01:12:01.680 --> 01:12:02.980
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson: Alice.

01:12:02.980 --> 01:12:04.280
Then they had the New Thing.

01:12:04.280 --> 01:12:08.500
And also he had a background in
architecture as well as in art.

01:12:08.500 --> 01:12:13.980
And there was Lou Stovall and
Die Stovall and Lloyd O'Neal

01:12:13.980 --> 01:12:21.200
who had been the workshop
which focused on printmaking

01:12:21.200 --> 01:12:24.180
and also graphic
design and the arts.

01:12:24.180 --> 01:12:27.890
And Lou did the typography
for it.

01:12:27.890 --> 01:12:30.180
He did the fonts and
everything for this book,

01:12:30.180 --> 01:12:32.920
the coloring book called
Children of Africa.

01:12:32.920 --> 01:12:36.670
But there were other -- the
Center for Black Education,

01:12:36.670 --> 01:12:42.820
Gaston Neal was an
incredible force.

01:12:42.820 --> 01:12:47.700
And Gaston considered
himself the spy

01:12:47.700 --> 01:12:50.270
of Brintano's and places.

01:12:50.270 --> 01:12:52.860
He would go down and then
come back to Drum and Spear

01:12:52.860 --> 01:12:55.510
and report what Brintano's
was selling

01:12:55.510 --> 01:12:58.150
and what they were
selling at 4:00.

01:12:58.150 --> 01:12:59.950
&gt;&gt; Tony Gittens: He
actually stole the books.

01:12:59.950 --> 01:13:01.270
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson:
Yes, thank you.

01:13:01.270 --> 01:13:02.570
Thank you, I was about to say.

01:13:02.570 --> 01:13:03.870
&gt;&gt; Tony Gittens: We're
here to tell the truth.

01:13:03.870 --> 01:13:05.170
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: Yes.

01:13:05.170 --> 01:13:07.030
&gt;&gt; Tony Gittens: Gaston
had skills and he would --

01:13:07.030 --> 01:13:09.040
[ Laughter ]

01:13:09.040 --> 01:13:10.930
And all of the sudden he'd show
up and he'd have all these,

01:13:10.930 --> 01:13:13.520
the newest books that we
could never afford to put.

01:13:13.520 --> 01:13:17.580
And he would make them available
to us at real discount prices,

01:13:17.580 --> 01:13:19.180
and we'd put them
on our shelves.

01:13:19.180 --> 01:13:21.340
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: However,
we got caught, let us remember.

01:13:21.340 --> 01:13:22.640
&gt;&gt;TG: Yes, oh.

01:13:22.640 --> 01:13:23.940
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: Remember
when the woman came up?

01:13:23.940 --> 01:13:25.240
The woman from Brintano's.

01:13:25.240 --> 01:13:27.000
Now this is before we get to
the story that you're saying.

01:13:27.000 --> 01:13:29.670
So we're still a small
store right on 14th Street.

01:13:29.670 --> 01:13:33.760
And she walks in and she
has a couple of the books.

01:13:33.760 --> 01:13:36.620
And she says -- oh, no, no.

01:13:36.620 --> 01:13:37.920
I'm sorry.

01:13:37.920 --> 01:13:41.200
She takes them off our
shelves and she shows it to us

01:13:41.200 --> 01:13:42.840
and she says, "No,
you'll see Brintano's" --

01:13:42.840 --> 01:13:45.510
because they had
Brintano's in them.

01:13:45.510 --> 01:13:48.230
[ Laughter ]

01:13:48.230 --> 01:13:51.040
And so she says, "Now,
we will not prosecute."

01:13:51.040 --> 01:13:52.590
Because she knew who he was.

01:13:52.590 --> 01:13:55.390
She said, "We will not
prosecute him, but you are not

01:13:55.390 --> 01:13:57.410
to buy any more books from him."

01:13:57.410 --> 01:13:58.710
And we didn't.

01:13:58.710 --> 01:14:00.520
But yeah, we called
him Sticky Fingers.

01:14:00.520 --> 01:14:01.820
Yeah.

01:14:01.820 --> 01:14:04.840
&gt;&gt; Didn't Topper Carew -- he
was involved in media later.

01:14:04.840 --> 01:14:06.160
He went to LA, didn't he?

01:14:06.160 --> 01:14:07.570
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: Yeah,
because I worked with him.

01:14:07.570 --> 01:14:08.870
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

01:14:08.870 --> 01:14:11.460
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: Topper Carew
also started the New Thing.

01:14:11.460 --> 01:14:12.760
&gt;&gt; Rainbow Media.

01:14:12.760 --> 01:14:14.060
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: Media Works.

01:14:14.060 --> 01:14:15.360
&gt;&gt; Tony Gittens: Yeah.

01:14:15.360 --> 01:14:16.660
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: So I went

01:14:16.660 --> 01:14:17.960
out after we started
the first series

01:14:17.960 --> 01:14:19.260
of what became the 14
hours of Eyes on the Prize.

01:14:19.260 --> 01:14:20.560
And then I go out and
I work with him in LA.

01:14:20.560 --> 01:14:22.820
And did you all at
PBS, did you fund him?

01:14:22.820 --> 01:14:24.120
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson: Yes.

01:14:24.120 --> 01:14:25.420
Yes, we funded him.

01:14:25.420 --> 01:14:26.720
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson:
That's right.

01:14:26.720 --> 01:14:28.020
Yeah.

01:14:28.020 --> 01:14:29.320
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson:
We funded him.

01:14:29.320 --> 01:14:30.620
He did a series of
children's programs,

01:14:30.620 --> 01:14:31.920
and he also did a series

01:14:31.920 --> 01:14:34.250
of other television
programs and films.

01:14:34.250 --> 01:14:37.650
His best-known film
was probably Car Wash.

01:14:37.650 --> 01:14:38.950
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson:
No, no, DC Cabs.

01:14:38.950 --> 01:14:40.250
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson: DC Cabs.

01:14:40.250 --> 01:14:41.550
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: Oh,
it was a horrible film.

01:14:41.550 --> 01:14:42.850
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson: DC Cabs.

01:14:42.850 --> 01:14:46.190
And he then was the person who
discovered Martin Lawrence.

01:14:46.190 --> 01:14:47.490
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

01:14:47.490 --> 01:14:49.340
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson: And later
became Martin's talent agent

01:14:49.340 --> 01:14:53.360
and then went on to become
the agent for a number of sort

01:14:53.360 --> 01:14:55.830
of high-profile comedians in LA.

01:14:55.830 --> 01:14:57.990
And he is now at MIT.

01:14:57.990 --> 01:15:02.680
&gt;&gt; Guha Shenkar: I just
wanted to point out,

01:15:02.680 --> 01:15:05.360
just had to make sure that
from the Library's perspective,

01:15:05.360 --> 01:15:06.810
stealing books is
not a good thing.

01:15:06.810 --> 01:15:09.010
Sorry.

01:15:09.010 --> 01:15:10.310
[ Laughter ]

01:15:10.310 --> 01:15:12.010
We need to make sure
that's on the record.

01:15:12.010 --> 01:15:13.980
[ Laughter ]

01:15:13.980 --> 01:15:16.300
Any other questions?

01:15:16.300 --> 01:15:20.400
&gt;&gt; I just wondered about your
relationship with libraries

01:15:20.400 --> 01:15:22.770
and outreach to libraries.

01:15:22.770 --> 01:15:26.030
I worked very briefly in
the beginning of my career

01:15:26.030 --> 01:15:27.330
and they didn't know
what to do with me

01:15:27.330 --> 01:15:28.630
because I was the new kid.

01:15:28.630 --> 01:15:32.220
And they put me in the library
in the black neighborhood.

01:15:32.220 --> 01:15:35.490
It was an incredible lesson
in the power of books.

01:15:35.490 --> 01:15:36.850
And we were like a place

01:15:36.850 --> 01:15:39.480
where the kids would
come after school.

01:15:39.480 --> 01:15:41.830
And they'd all stream in and
they were just so excited.

01:15:41.830 --> 01:15:48.630
And so I wondered how your
interaction went with libraries.

01:15:48.630 --> 01:15:50.390
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: I
can say that there was

01:15:50.390 --> 01:15:53.970
at that point a black
caucus of the ALA,

01:15:53.970 --> 01:15:56.110
the American Librarians
Association.

01:15:56.110 --> 01:15:57.870
And so we would do
conferences with them

01:15:57.870 --> 01:16:00.590
and we would present a display.

01:16:00.590 --> 01:16:04.290
As I said, we would take the
exhibits other places outside

01:16:04.290 --> 01:16:05.590
the store.

01:16:05.590 --> 01:16:07.020
And so we would bring some
of the children's books

01:16:07.020 --> 01:16:09.620
that we had, and they were
very supportive of us.

01:16:09.620 --> 01:16:11.290
I don't know of any
-- maybe you all do.

01:16:11.290 --> 01:16:13.510
I don't know of any
direct relationship we had

01:16:13.510 --> 01:16:17.550
between the store and the
librarians except to say

01:16:17.550 --> 01:16:19.950
that they would often come
into the store and check

01:16:19.950 --> 01:16:21.250
out some of the titles.

01:16:21.250 --> 01:16:25.350
Because of course, they're
not being shown the titles

01:16:25.350 --> 01:16:26.730
by the publishers.

01:16:26.730 --> 01:16:28.160
And we were.

01:16:28.160 --> 01:16:29.460
I mean, yeah.

01:16:29.460 --> 01:16:30.760
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson: But
it's interesting too

01:16:30.760 --> 01:16:32.060
in our later lives.

01:16:32.060 --> 01:16:37.570
I think that our appreciation
for education and you know,

01:16:37.570 --> 01:16:41.040
big E, small e, is just
so profound that then

01:16:41.040 --> 01:16:43.980
that continues our
relationship with organizations

01:16:43.980 --> 01:16:47.370
like Debra Mincart's
Teaching for Change.

01:16:47.370 --> 01:16:51.200
And also with work that
goes into the library.

01:16:51.200 --> 01:16:54.040
For example, whether it's
Eyes on the Prize or some

01:16:54.040 --> 01:16:57.570
of the other documentary
or other films that we did,

01:16:57.570 --> 01:16:59.540
we'd always make provisions

01:16:59.540 --> 01:17:03.710
that there would be what we call
outreach or other extensions

01:17:03.710 --> 01:17:07.940
of this work so that it would
go then either on the internet

01:17:07.940 --> 01:17:10.960
or it would have materials
that would go for use

01:17:10.960 --> 01:17:14.200
by community groups
and for kids.

01:17:14.200 --> 01:17:15.980
&gt;&gt; Guha Shenkar:
Other questions?

01:17:15.980 --> 01:17:18.770
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: But we love
librarians, let me just say.

01:17:18.770 --> 01:17:20.070
We do.

01:17:20.070 --> 01:17:21.370
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson: Yes,
librarians are very special.

01:17:21.370 --> 01:17:26.400
&gt;&gt; Guha Shenkar: And librarians
love you, thank you very much.

01:17:26.400 --> 01:17:27.700
Yes, sir?

01:17:27.700 --> 01:17:29.000
&gt;&gt; Thank you for this panel.

01:17:29.000 --> 01:17:32.760
I don't necessarily know if I
have a question or a comment.

01:17:32.760 --> 01:17:38.390
I'm sure it's going to morph
into wanting, begging an answer.

01:17:38.390 --> 01:17:40.060
My father's from
Greenwood, Mississippi.

01:17:40.060 --> 01:17:41.530
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: Oh, okay.

01:17:41.530 --> 01:17:45.420
&gt;&gt; And my name is
Julius Rosenwald.

01:17:45.420 --> 01:17:51.220
And I just wonder -- I didn't
know who Julius Rosenwald was

01:17:51.220 --> 01:17:53.720
until I became in my 30's.

01:17:53.720 --> 01:17:59.380
And so when I read about
this symposium, I said, "Oh,

01:17:59.380 --> 01:18:01.850
well let me get down there."

01:18:01.850 --> 01:18:08.580
Because I just saw
Fahrenheit 11/9.

01:18:08.580 --> 01:18:09.880
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: How is it?

01:18:09.880 --> 01:18:11.180
&gt;&gt; It was wonderful.

01:18:11.180 --> 01:18:12.480
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: Okay.

01:18:12.480 --> 01:18:13.780
&gt;&gt; And I want to
say you were in it,

01:18:13.780 --> 01:18:15.080
but you were speaking
about the kids.

01:18:15.080 --> 01:18:16.380
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: Yes.

01:18:16.380 --> 01:18:17.680
&gt;&gt; And that's my question.

01:18:17.680 --> 01:18:19.150
There are a lot of
organizations.

01:18:19.150 --> 01:18:22.870
For years I was involved
with AFL, CIO, NAACP.

01:18:22.870 --> 01:18:29.340
And so there are a lot
of organizations now

01:18:29.340 --> 01:18:33.960
that have not usurped you

01:18:33.960 --> 01:18:37.260
but are doing pieces
of what you're doing.

01:18:37.260 --> 01:18:40.070
Or pieces of what
NAACP is doing.

01:18:40.070 --> 01:18:41.370
And some people would argue

01:18:41.370 --> 01:18:44.630
that they're doing
it more efficiently.

01:18:44.630 --> 01:18:47.450
But I think that they're
not doing everything

01:18:47.450 --> 01:18:48.750
that you're doing.

01:18:48.750 --> 01:18:50.050
See, you had to do everything.

01:18:50.050 --> 01:18:51.350
Now you have organizations
that are just going

01:18:51.350 --> 01:18:53.460
to do a little bit of
it, a little bit of it.

01:18:53.460 --> 01:18:56.200
So they can specialize.

01:18:56.200 --> 01:19:05.870
But I think one of the concerns
is that students, when they want

01:19:05.870 --> 01:19:09.700
to get involved, and
I see that you all --

01:19:09.700 --> 01:19:11.730
I was reading your bios.

01:19:11.730 --> 01:19:16.640
And you know, you had successful
careers, so how do students now

01:19:16.640 --> 01:19:18.430
that they want to get
involved and they still have

01:19:18.430 --> 01:19:22.710
to be concerned about their
livelihoods, how do they make

01:19:22.710 --> 01:19:25.330
that transition to
that capitalism?

01:19:25.330 --> 01:19:29.930
How do they -- you
know, you can't go

01:19:29.930 --> 01:19:33.750
through your life
being an activist

01:19:33.750 --> 01:19:36.660
without being able
to sustain yourself.

01:19:36.660 --> 01:19:40.000
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: But
I think there are times

01:19:40.000 --> 01:19:43.130
when we can do both.

01:19:43.130 --> 01:19:44.430
&gt;&gt; But how do you do that?

01:19:44.430 --> 01:19:45.890
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: Okay,
let me just say that all

01:19:45.890 --> 01:19:47.690
of us have figured
out ways to do both.

01:19:47.690 --> 01:19:48.990
&gt;&gt; Tony Gittens: That's correct.

01:19:48.990 --> 01:19:50.290
&gt;&gt; Right.

01:19:50.290 --> 01:19:51.590
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: So I'm
going to answer your question.

01:19:51.590 --> 01:19:54.720
One of the things that has
been very helpful to me is

01:19:54.720 --> 01:19:56.930
that I knew nothing
about filmmaking, right?

01:19:56.930 --> 01:19:58.660
Nothing. Diddly-squat.

01:19:58.660 --> 01:20:01.730
I go in and Henry says, "Okay,
I'm starting what is going

01:20:01.730 --> 01:20:04.540
to be a one-hour documentary
on the Civil Rights Movement."

01:20:04.540 --> 01:20:05.840
It becomes 14.

01:20:05.840 --> 01:20:07.140
Who knew?

01:20:07.140 --> 01:20:09.230
But I brought the skills
of the movement with me.

01:20:09.230 --> 01:20:10.590
That's what got me in the door.

01:20:10.590 --> 01:20:13.270
Because I knew nothing
about filmmaking, right?

01:20:13.270 --> 01:20:17.860
I knew how to interview, because
I had operated the 800 line

01:20:17.860 --> 01:20:19.160
for SNCC.

01:20:19.160 --> 01:20:20.750
So when people are calling
in about church burnings

01:20:20.750 --> 01:20:25.600
or killings, I knew how to take
the information and then give it

01:20:25.600 --> 01:20:27.970
to an FBI that did not care.

01:20:27.970 --> 01:20:29.920
The bottom line was
though that the skills

01:20:29.920 --> 01:20:31.980
that you get you can
take other places.

01:20:31.980 --> 01:20:34.710
The problem is you
really have to be grounded

01:20:34.710 --> 01:20:36.990
in knowing why you're
where you are.

01:20:36.990 --> 01:20:42.810
So I always -- even when I went
into -- Blackside was easier.

01:20:42.810 --> 01:20:44.800
Even Northern Life
Productions, I go into that,

01:20:44.800 --> 01:20:46.900
we do the Orangeburg
Massacre and other films.

01:20:46.900 --> 01:20:51.330
I'm working now for the
National Park Service.

01:20:51.330 --> 01:20:54.490
I and the team had done the
Little Rock Nine Orientation

01:20:54.490 --> 01:20:57.070
films for Little Rock
Central High School.

01:20:57.070 --> 01:20:59.120
Now we're doing summer, right?

01:20:59.120 --> 01:21:00.440
But it's the skills
of the movement

01:21:00.440 --> 01:21:02.070
that are bringing me in there.

01:21:02.070 --> 01:21:05.490
I think there are enough
ways that you can do --

01:21:05.490 --> 01:21:08.140
and sometimes it's not
going into capitalism.

01:21:08.140 --> 01:21:10.910
I never think of myself
as figuring out a way

01:21:10.910 --> 01:21:12.640
to become a capitalist, okay?

01:21:12.640 --> 01:21:17.080
It is how do I bring my values
into whatever situation I'm in?

01:21:17.080 --> 01:21:20.330
And how am I able
to pay the rent?

01:21:20.330 --> 01:21:23.790
And maybe that's something
that others can talk about.

01:21:23.790 --> 01:21:26.860
&gt;&gt; Tony Gittens: When
we're born, we grow up,

01:21:26.860 --> 01:21:29.450
we're told that there
are certain rules,

01:21:29.450 --> 01:21:31.800
that there's a certain track.

01:21:31.800 --> 01:21:34.800
That if you behave, you play
by the rules, you don't bump

01:21:34.800 --> 01:21:38.910
into the walls too much,
that you're going to be okay.

01:21:38.910 --> 01:21:43.770
And you find out -- we found
out that those rules are made

01:21:43.770 --> 01:21:46.700
up by other people just like us.

01:21:46.700 --> 01:21:51.480
And we can therefore
-- once you know that,

01:21:51.480 --> 01:21:54.190
you can pretty much do whatever.

01:21:54.190 --> 01:21:58.350
You know, there's no --
there aren't any rules.

01:21:58.350 --> 01:22:00.160
So you make up your own.

01:22:00.160 --> 01:22:02.800
I mean, at least
it's my approach.

01:22:02.800 --> 01:22:04.690
I don't know about
the folks down there.

01:22:04.690 --> 01:22:07.630
But I don't know anything
about making movies.

01:22:07.630 --> 01:22:09.440
And I've spent a good part

01:22:09.440 --> 01:22:12.810
of my professional life
putting on film festivals.

01:22:12.810 --> 01:22:16.050
You know? I don't know
how to do any of that.

01:22:16.050 --> 01:22:18.550
I mean, Judy just talked
about what she knows.

01:22:18.550 --> 01:22:19.850
The lady over there,

01:22:19.850 --> 01:22:24.380
I know she's bright
as can be, you know.

01:22:24.380 --> 01:22:26.570
But you sort of --
once you sort of --

01:22:26.570 --> 01:22:29.190
we spent a lot of the time
with things we were talking

01:22:29.190 --> 01:22:32.310
about up here pushing
against the rules,

01:22:32.310 --> 01:22:34.000
somebody else's rules.

01:22:34.000 --> 01:22:36.210
They said, "Look, don't do that.

01:22:36.210 --> 01:22:40.060
If you just go to school
and get the master's degree

01:22:40.060 --> 01:22:42.850
and da-da-da-da-da, you know"
[laughs], if you just do that,

01:22:42.850 --> 01:22:45.470
it's going to be okay.

01:22:45.470 --> 01:22:47.210
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: And she's
from Greenwood, by the way.

01:22:47.210 --> 01:22:48.890
&gt;&gt; Tony Gittens: And
she's from Greenwood.

01:22:48.890 --> 01:22:50.190
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson:

01:22:50.190 --> 01:22:52.580
Strong movement family
in Greenwood, yes.

01:22:52.580 --> 01:22:53.880
&gt;&gt; Tony Gittens: You know?

01:22:53.880 --> 01:22:57.390
And then you find out
it's just somebody else

01:22:57.390 --> 01:22:58.690
who made the rules up.

01:22:58.690 --> 01:23:00.400
Well, if they make them up, we
can make up our own rules too.

01:23:00.400 --> 01:23:02.040
We're going to start
a bookstore.

01:23:02.040 --> 01:23:04.930
Hey, and then we're going
to start a press over here.

01:23:04.930 --> 01:23:07.090
You know? What do we know
about doing that stuff?

01:23:07.090 --> 01:23:12.180
What we knew is you know,
we knew that we didn't

01:23:12.180 --> 01:23:15.200
like the things -- we
didn't like the way

01:23:15.200 --> 01:23:17.250
that they're treating not
only us, but other people,

01:23:17.250 --> 01:23:19.090
and we were going to do
something about that.

01:23:19.090 --> 01:23:24.120
It bothered us to our core the
way they would oppress people

01:23:24.120 --> 01:23:27.280
and us and our friends and
people that we didn't even know.

01:23:27.280 --> 01:23:29.070
That we didn't even know.

01:23:29.070 --> 01:23:31.530
And that pissed us
off, for sure.

01:23:31.530 --> 01:23:33.170
It pissed us off.

01:23:33.170 --> 01:23:36.000
And we said, "We're going
to do something about that."

01:23:36.000 --> 01:23:37.610
That's what we knew.

01:23:37.610 --> 01:23:39.660
That's what we knew.

01:23:39.660 --> 01:23:42.050
I'm only saying that
because all of us,

01:23:42.050 --> 01:23:44.320
we get young people
coming to us.

01:23:44.320 --> 01:23:48.040
When they come to me, they ask
advice, "Well, how do I do it?"

01:23:48.040 --> 01:23:49.340
And I have no answers for them.

01:23:49.340 --> 01:23:51.640
I don't know what to tell them.

01:23:54.040 --> 01:23:55.520
&gt;&gt; The reason I asked
that question is

01:23:55.520 --> 01:23:58.770
because now I'm a
member of 100 Black Men

01:23:58.770 --> 01:24:00.070
of Prince George County.

01:24:00.070 --> 01:24:02.760
And we have all these
brown kids.

01:24:02.760 --> 01:24:09.790
And so we want -- I want to
be able to have them know

01:24:09.790 --> 01:24:13.540
who you are, and to know --

01:24:13.540 --> 01:24:17.250
I don't know if they should
know that they'll be okay.

01:24:17.250 --> 01:24:21.670
But I do want them to have
tools in their toolkit

01:24:21.670 --> 01:24:23.760
so that they can
make that transition,

01:24:23.760 --> 01:24:27.360
so that they are not
afraid to be true

01:24:27.360 --> 01:24:30.170
to who they are and
be activists.

01:24:30.170 --> 01:24:37.150
In the 9/11 movie, most of the
kids, those were white kids.

01:24:37.150 --> 01:24:42.140
And I'm not saying that --
well, they are privileged.

01:24:42.140 --> 01:24:45.200
And our kids are
brown and black.

01:24:45.200 --> 01:24:50.920
And the target population
may or may not go to college.

01:24:50.920 --> 01:24:53.010
And so I don't know if they're
going to have those skills,

01:24:53.010 --> 01:24:54.310
but I want them to
have those skills.

01:24:54.310 --> 01:24:55.610
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: But
there are other films

01:24:55.610 --> 01:24:58.130
about young people like
them that you can show them.

01:24:58.130 --> 01:24:59.430
&gt;&gt; Tony Gittens: Right.

01:24:59.430 --> 01:25:00.730
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson:
And I don't know --

01:25:00.730 --> 01:25:05.060
Debra, Jennifer,
some suggestions?

01:25:06.510 --> 01:25:10.190
[ Inaudible ]

01:25:10.190 --> 01:25:11.490
I mean, part of the problem is

01:25:11.490 --> 01:25:12.860
that we only see
the Parkland kids.

01:25:12.860 --> 01:25:14.240
There were kids organizing
before them,

01:25:14.240 --> 01:25:15.540
there's kids organizing now.

01:25:15.540 --> 01:25:16.840
&gt;&gt; Right.

01:25:16.840 --> 01:25:18.140
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: Thankfully,
they've often allied with

01:25:18.140 --> 01:25:19.440
and made sure those other --

01:25:19.440 --> 01:25:21.670
there's the Dream
Defenders which you can learn

01:25:21.670 --> 01:25:23.190
about them at the SNCC Gateway.

01:25:23.190 --> 01:25:24.490
There's the film
Precious Knowledge

01:25:24.490 --> 01:25:26.600
about the young people
in Tucson.

01:25:26.600 --> 01:25:27.950
There's other documentaries.

01:25:27.950 --> 01:25:29.250
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson: Yes.

01:25:29.250 --> 01:25:30.950
&gt;&gt; Guha Shenkar: All right.

01:25:30.950 --> 01:25:32.600
We're just now going
to wrap it up.

01:25:32.600 --> 01:25:34.910
But I want to get maybe the
historian's perspective on this,

01:25:34.910 --> 01:25:36.210
not because it's the last one,

01:25:36.210 --> 01:25:39.090
but because it's the stepping
back and looking at things

01:25:39.090 --> 01:25:42.040
from a broader perspective.

01:25:42.040 --> 01:25:44.700
These questions have all
raised some interesting things.

01:25:44.700 --> 01:25:46.610
We could probably do
another two panels on this.

01:25:46.610 --> 01:25:49.260
But what is your
takeaway as a historian

01:25:49.260 --> 01:25:52.850
that might be interesting for
all of us to share with us?

01:25:52.850 --> 01:25:56.390
&gt;&gt; Joshua Davis: Maybe to
connect it to the last question,

01:25:56.390 --> 01:25:58.110
to me what's really amazing is

01:25:58.110 --> 01:26:03.540
to see what all the people
coming out of SNCC did

01:26:03.540 --> 01:26:05.320
in the rest of their lives.

01:26:05.320 --> 01:26:10.910
And I think that is
really amazing to see

01:26:10.910 --> 01:26:14.620
that so many people coming
out of SNCC, very creative

01:26:14.620 --> 01:26:20.840
and finding different ways
to continue their work

01:26:20.840 --> 01:26:23.940
through different agencies,
vehicles, organizations.

01:26:23.940 --> 01:26:25.240
I mean, it's really profound.

01:26:25.240 --> 01:26:28.000
If we just looked at
these three people here,

01:26:28.000 --> 01:26:30.990
but then if you throw John
Lewis in and [inaudible].

01:26:30.990 --> 01:26:34.250
I mean, it's just endless.

01:26:34.250 --> 01:26:35.660
The list is just endless.

01:26:35.660 --> 01:26:37.540
You see what all the
people did, yeah.

01:26:37.540 --> 01:26:38.840
&gt;&gt; Tony Gittens: Stokely.

01:26:38.840 --> 01:26:40.730
&gt;&gt; Joshua Davis: And I think
that's part of the answer

01:26:40.730 --> 01:26:45.520
to your question, is looking
at someone like Bob Moses

01:26:45.520 --> 01:26:46.820
who did Radical Equations.

01:26:46.820 --> 01:26:48.650
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: Yes.

01:26:48.650 --> 01:26:49.950
&gt;&gt; Joshua Davis:
There are things

01:26:49.950 --> 01:26:51.470
that maybe our society
doesn't think of as part

01:26:51.470 --> 01:26:55.460
of the Civil Rights Movement,
a book about bringing math

01:26:55.460 --> 01:26:57.400
to underprivileged students.

01:26:57.400 --> 01:26:59.020
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: And who
has the Algebra Project.

01:26:59.020 --> 01:27:00.320
&gt;&gt; Joshua Davis: Yeah.

01:27:00.320 --> 01:27:03.800
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: Which is
coming to DC public schools.

01:27:03.800 --> 01:27:05.100
&gt;&gt; Joshua Davis: Yeah.

01:27:05.100 --> 01:27:08.480
That would be my main
kind of answer to that,

01:27:08.480 --> 01:27:10.160
is that things take
different forms.

01:27:10.160 --> 01:27:15.000
But the creativity is what
allowed so many people coming

01:27:15.000 --> 01:27:16.990
out of SNCC and just
the movement in general

01:27:16.990 --> 01:27:18.530
to continue doing
what they're doing.

01:27:18.530 --> 01:27:22.610
Not necessarily get rich,
but to survive and sustain

01:27:22.610 --> 01:27:25.710
and even prosper in the
fullest sense of that word.

01:27:25.710 --> 01:27:27.010
&gt;&gt; Guha Shenkar: And as long
as we're talking about it,

01:27:27.010 --> 01:27:28.310
there are three other veterans

01:27:28.310 --> 01:27:31.660
of the Civil Rights
Movement here with us.

01:27:31.660 --> 01:27:34.810
Charlene Kranz, [inaudible]
right back there,

01:27:34.810 --> 01:27:37.400
all of whom have been introduced

01:27:37.400 --> 01:27:40.740
for the Civil Rights
History Project.

01:27:40.740 --> 01:27:42.850
So if you're looking for models,
that's one place to look.

01:27:42.850 --> 01:27:45.270
The SNCC Digital Gateway at
Duke University is another place

01:27:45.270 --> 01:27:46.570
to look.

01:27:46.570 --> 01:27:47.870
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: I have
fliers for those who want them.

01:27:47.870 --> 01:27:50.630
&gt;&gt; Guha Shenkar: And so
if you're taking cards,

01:27:50.630 --> 01:27:51.930
you might as well take a copy

01:27:51.930 --> 01:27:54.310
of Josh Clark Davis's
book with you.

01:27:54.310 --> 01:27:55.910
It's right out there
in the lobby.

01:27:55.910 --> 01:27:59.390
It's actually in the
gift shop now, sorry.

01:27:59.390 --> 01:28:03.010
So that's quite all right.

01:28:03.010 --> 01:28:04.310
[ Inaudible ]

01:28:04.310 --> 01:28:07.020
And I'm going to bring it to a
close because I have the card

01:28:07.020 --> 01:28:09.590
which says two minutes and I've
just given myself 30 seconds

01:28:09.590 --> 01:28:11.030
to say --

01:28:11.030 --> 01:28:13.040
[ Laughter ]

01:28:13.040 --> 01:28:14.340
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson:
Thank you, Guha.

01:28:14.340 --> 01:28:15.840
&gt;&gt; Judy Richardson: Thank you.

01:28:15.840 --> 01:28:18.040
[ Applause ]

01:28:18.040 --> 01:28:19.340
&gt;&gt; Guha Shenkar: It's our
